{"title_page": "California Dreamin'", "text_new": "{{Redirect|California Dreaming||California Dreamin' (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      = Disco de vinilo - California dreamin'.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Mamas and the Papas]]\n| album      = [[If You Can Believe Your Eyes and Ears]]\n| B-side     = Somebody Groovy\n| released   = December 8, 1965\n| format     = [[Phonograph record|Vinyl record]] (7\") 45 RPM\n| recorded   = November 4, 1965, Western Recorders, Hollywood\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Sunshine pop]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Dictionnaire des Musiciens: (Les Dictionnaires d'Universalis)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9yKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT3635|date=October 27, 2015|publisher=Encyclopaedia Universalis|isbn=978-2-85229-140-9|page=3635}}</ref>|[[folk rock]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-folk-rock-music-2521910|title= What is Folk-Rock Music?|last= Fontenot|first= Robert|date= October 29, 2015|website= ThoughtCo.|publisher= [[About.com]]|access-date= March 12, 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=38}}\n| label      = [[Dunhill Records]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phillips]]\n| producer   = [[Lou Adler]]\n| prev_title = [[Go Where You Wanna Go]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Monday, Monday]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       =\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=California Dreamin.ogg\n|title=\"California Dreamin'\"\n|description=[[The Mamas and the Papas]]' \"California Dreamin'\" from their debut album, ''[[If You Can Believe Your Eyes and Ears]]''.\n|filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n\"'''California Dreamin'''<nowiki/>'\" is a song written by [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]] and [[Michelle Phillips]] and was first recorded by [[Barry McGuire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/take-two/2013/03/05/30786/how-the-iconic-tune-california-dreamin-came-to-be/|title=Take Two|author=Southern California Public Radio|work=Southern California Public Radio}}</ref> However, the best-known version is by [[the Mamas and the Papas]], who sang backup on the original version and released it as a single in 1965. The song is No. 89 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'s}} list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/the-mamas-and-the-papas-california-dreamin-20110526 |title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416005906/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1 |archivedate=April 16, 2007 |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> The lyrics of the song express the narrator's longing for the warmth of [[Los Angeles]] during a cold winter in [[New York City]].\n\nThe song became a signpost of the [[California Sound]],<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bisbort|first1=Alan|last2=Puterbaugh|first2=Parke|title=California Beaches: The Best Places to Swim, Play, Eat, and Stay|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5D-egP4JWsEC&pg=PA172|year=2009|publisher=Avalon Travel|isbn=978-1-56691-614-1|p=172}}</ref> heralding the arrival of the nascent [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/eagles-fleetwood-mac-selected-for-hall-of-fame-19971028 |title=Eagles, Fleetwood Mac Selected for Hall of Fame &#124; Music News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=1997-10-28 |accessdate=2014-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1146306 |title='California Dreamin,' Present at the Creation (Archived Radio Program) |last=Stamberg|first=Susan|date=2002-07-08 |website=NPR.org |publisher=NPR |accessdate=2014-04-29}}</ref>\n\n\"California Dreamin'\" was certified as a [[Gold Record]] (single) by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] in June 1966<ref>{{cite web|title=California Dreamin'|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|website=RIAA.com|publisher=The Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=2014-07-11|quote=The RIAA Database may require user input}}</ref> and was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=California Dreamin'|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#c|website=grammy.org|publisher=The Recording Academy|accessdate=2014-07-11|quote=CALIFORNIA DREAMIN' The Mamas And The Papas Dunhill (1966) (Single) Inducted 2001}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe song was written in 1963 while [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]] and [[Michelle Phillips]] were living in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottmckenzie.info/interview-5.html|title=1995 Interview (5) - \"California Dreaming\" - Scott McKenzie|website=www.scottmckenzie.info}}</ref> He dreamed about the song and woke her up to help him write it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribut.clothing/monday-night-blues/ep61/ |title=TRIBUT Presents: Monday Night Blues|work=Monday Night Blues}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2016|title=California Dreamin' by The Mamas & the Papas Songfacts|publisher=}}</ref> At the time, John and Michelle Phillips were members of the folk group the New Journeymen, which evolved into [[the Mamas and the Papas]].\n\nThey earned their first record contract after being introduced to [[Lou Adler]], the head of [[Dunhill Records]], by [[Barry McGuire]]. In thanks to Adler, they sang the backing vocals to \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} with members of the session band [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|The Wrecking Crew]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Kent |last=Hartman |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749/page/261 261\u2013263] |year=2012 |title=The Wrecking Crew |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749 |url-access=registration |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press|St. Martin's Griffin]] |isbn=978-1-250-03046-7}}</ref> on McGuire's album ''This Precious Time''. The Mamas and the Papas then recorded their own version using the same instrumental and backing vocal tracks, to which they added new vocals<ref name=\"pc33\">{{cite web |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19792/m1/ |title=Show 33 - Revolt of the Fat Angel: American musicians respond to the British invaders. [Part 1] |work=The University of North Texas Digital Library |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> and an [[alto flute]] solo by [[Bud Shank]]. The guitar introduction was performed by [[P. F. Sloan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ |title=Classic Tracks: The Mamas & The Papas' \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} |last=Daily |first=Dan |date=July 1, 2004 |publisher=Mix Magazine |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204034801/http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ |archivedate=February 4, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> McGuire's original vocal can be briefly heard on the left channel at the beginning of the record, having not been completely erased.<ref>[[Pete Frame|Rock Family Trees]], [[BBC]], interview with McGuire, 1999. McGuire's original harmonica solo can also just be made out under the flute solo.</ref>\n\nThe single was released in late 1965 but was not an immediate breakthrough. After gaining little attention in Los Angeles upon its release, a radio station in Boston was the catalyst to break the song nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html |title=California Dreamin' |work=npr.org |date=July 8, 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218014724/http://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html |archivedate=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 6, 2012}}</ref> After making its chart debut in January 1966,<ref name=\"Sullivan2013\">{{cite book|last=Sullivan|first=Steve|title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA483|date=4 October 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8296-6|pages=483\u2013}}</ref> the song peaked at No. 4 in March on both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], lasting 17 weeks, and ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'', lasting 20 weeks.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bronson|first1=Fred|title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits|date=1988|publisher=Billboard Publications, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-7545-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofnbro00bron/page/195 195]|edition=Paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofnbro00bron/page/195}}</ref> California Dreamin{{'}} also reached number 23 on the UK charts upon its original release, and re-charted after its use in a [[Carling O'Keefe|Carling Premier]] commercial in 1997, peaking at number nine there.<ref>{{cite book| first=Hamish| last=Pringle| title=Celebrity Sells| year=2004| publisher=John Wiley & Sons Ltd| location=Chichester UK| page=[https://archive.org/details/celebritysells00hami/page/36 36]| isbn=0-470-86850-3| url=https://archive.org/details/celebritysells00hami/page/36}}</ref>\n\nThe song is repeatedly used in the 1994 [[Hong Kong]] film ''[[Chungking Express]]'' as a central plot point.<ref>[https://film.avclub.com/song-and-vision-no-5-california-dreamin-and-chungki-1798217949 Song And Vision No. 5: &quot;California Dreamin&#39;&quot; and Chungking Express], Steven Hyden</ref>\n\nMichelle Phillips wrote the lyrics, \"Well, I got down on my knees, and I pretend to pray,\" but Cass Elliot had been singing \"I began to pray\" until corrected by Phillips when they were touring. She sang \"began\" on the original recording.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZVay1RYazI</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n===America version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = singleyy474r7437ft\n| artist     = [[America (band)|America]]g  \n| album      = <br> [[California Dreaming (1979 film)|California Dreaming]] soundtrack\n| B-side     = \"See It My Way\" (by F.D.R.)\n| released   = March 1979\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = Studio 55 (Hollyfwood) 1978\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[soft rodck]]\n| length     = 2:44d\n| label      = [[American fdInternational Pictures|American International]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phil55lips]]\n| producer   = [[Dewey Bunnell]], [[gfbGerry Beckley]]5\n| prev_title = Don't Cry Baby\n| prev_year  = 1977f\n| next_title = Onlyd Game in Town\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\nIn the spring of 1979 the band [[America (band)|America]] reached {{Numero|56}}  on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] with their remake of \"California Dreamin'\" which was the first studio recording by America as the duo of [[Gerry Bec45t 545kley]] and [[Dewey Bunnell]] without third founding member [[Dan Peek]], who had departed the group in 1977. Bunnell \u2013 who sang lead \u2013 and Beckley \u2013 who sang background \u2013 self-produced the track which featured America's touring musicians: David Dickey, drummer Willie Leacox, guitarist Michael Woods, percussionist Tom Walsh, and Jim Calire who played keyboards and also saxophone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labibledelawestcoast.blogspot.ca/2016/11/|title=La Bible de la Westcoast Music - Cool Night -|website=labibledelawestcoast.blogspot.ca}}</ref><ref name=\"Access Backstage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accessbackstage.com/america/song/song157.htm|title=Lyrics: California Dreamin'|website=www.accessbackstage.com}}</ref>\n\nAmerica had performed \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} at least on occasion in concert as early as 1974,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.setlist.fm/stats/songs/the-mamas-and-the-papas-bd6053e.html?song=California+Dreamin'|title=California Dreamin' by The Mamas & the Papas Song Statistics - setlist.fm|website=www.setlist.fm}}</ref> \"California Dreamin'\" being a sentimental favorite of the band's members having been a setlist staple of the [[cover band]] in which all three had performed while [[London Central Elementary High School|London Central High School]] students in the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite book|title=An American Band: the America Story|last=Peak|first=Dan|year=2004 |publisher=Xulon Press|isbn=1-594679-29-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theslateonline.com/article/2018/02/eeoz41m20k5nn0i|title=Fans brave winter weather for America performance|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/america-brings-sounds-of-summer-to-casino-show-1.1725657|title=America brings sounds of summer to casino show|first=Kristen|last=Gaydos|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucaecho.net/news/america-performs-hit-a-horse-with-no-name/|title=America Performs Hit 'A Horse With No Name'|date=November 14, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The recording of \"California Dreamin'\" by America was specifically made to play under the closing credits of the [[American International Pictures]] (AIP) movie release ''[[California Dreaming (1979 film)|California Dreaming]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornsection.blogspot.com/2011/08/film-review-california-dreaming-1979.html|title=The Horn Section: Film Review: CALIFORNIA DREAMING (1979)|first=Hal|last=Horn|date=August 24, 2011|publisher=}}</ref>  which had been shot in the final months of 1977 for release in the summer of 1978 although the movie would in fact be held back from wide release until 16 March 1979<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56231|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref> with America recording the song \"California Dreamin'\" in the autumn of 1978:<ref name=\"Shirlebrities\">''Detroit Free Press'' \"Shirlebreties\" by Shirley Eder 30 November 1978 p.17B</ref> Beckley and Bunnell agreed to record the song after being (at least partially) shown the movie \u2013 <small>(Gerry Beckley quote:)</small> \"We liked what we saw\"<ref name=\"Access Backstage\"/> \u2013 and the track was recorded at Studio 55 (Hollywood): <small>(Gerry Beckley quote:)</small>\"We did it more as a rock thing [compared to the original], [with] a full sound but reliant on the harmonies.\"<ref name=\"Access Backstage\"/>\n\nThe track was originally scheduled for a 15 January 1979 release<ref name=\"Shirlebrities\"/> which was delayed until after AIP's February 1979 pacting with [[Casablanca Records]] to distribute the  ''California Dreaming'' soundtrack, Casablanca having recently managed to bolster the modest success of the film ''[[Thank God It's Friday (film)|Thank God It's Friday]]'' through a hit soundtrack album:<ref>''Billboard'' Vol 91 #9 (3 Mar 1979) \"Soundtrack lp for Casablanca\" p. 19</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Harris| first=Larry| title=And Party Every Day: the inside story of Casablanca Records| year=2009| publisher=Backbeat Books| location=Milwaukee WI| isbn=9781617133831}}</ref> the recording of \"California Dreamin'\" by America was therefore given parallel release with the movie, another soundtrack item: \"See It My Way\" by session group F.D.R., serving as [[A-side and B-side#B-side|B-side]]. Both the America single and (in April 1978) the soundtrack album were issued by AIP on its own label (distributed by Casablanca): outside the US and Canada, Casablanca acted as label of release.\n \nBy the spring of 1979 America were involved in sessions for their [[Capitol Records]] debut album ''[[Silent Letter (album)|Silent Letter]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessbackstage.com/america/hist04.htm|title=Comprehensive History: America Revisited - Part 4|website=www.accessbackstage.com}}</ref> and were either unable or uninterested in promoting their version of \"California Dreamin'\" which single proved unable to buoy its parent film's faltering box office take. However the publicity inherent in the film's release was evidently enough to afford minor hit status to America's soundtrack item (heard in the film's trailer, America's \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} was also cited in the movie's poster), and despite its lowly chart peak America's \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} remake would be more successful than any of their first five Capitol single releases none of which ranked in the Hot 100 (the band's sixth Capitol single release: \"[[You Can Do Magic (song)|You Can Do Magic]]\", would in 1982 afford the band a sole latterday Top Ten hit).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicvf.com/America.art|title=America Songs \u2022\u2022\u2022 Top Songs / Chart Singles Discography \u2022\u2022\u2022 Music VF, US & UK hits charts|website=www.musicvf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/artist/america|title=America Discography - USA - 45cat|website=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n\n\"California Dreamin{{'\"}} continued to be featured in America's live gigs eventually being established as a mandatory America concert title.<ref>http://www.conncerts.com/americareview.html</ref> A live performance of the song by America is featured on ''[[In Concert (1995 America album)|In Concert]]'' the band's 1996 album release of a 1982 live gig.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/king-biscuit-flower-hour-mw0000178321|title=King Biscuit Flower Hour - America - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref> The band's 1978 recording has been included on the 2000 America retrospective box set ''[[Highway (America album)|Highway: 30 Years Of America]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/highway-30-years-of-america-mw0000086640|title=Highway: 30 Years of America - America - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref> also being featured in 2001 on ''[[The Complete Greatest Hits (America album)|The Complete Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/america-mn0000019297|title=America - Biography, Albums, Streaming Links - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n===Beach Boys version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      = California_Dreamin'_Beach_Boys.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Beach Boys]]\n| album      = [[Made in U.S.A. (The Beach Boys album)|Made in U.S.A.]]\n| B-side     = [[Lady Lynda|Lady Liberty]]\n| released   = 1986\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = May 1986\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 3:10\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phillips]]\n| producer   = [[Terry Melcher]]\n| prev_title = [[Rock 'n' Roll to the Rescue]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = Happy Endings\n| next_year  = 1987\n}}\n\n====Background====\nThe Beach Boys recorded \"California Dreamin'\" in 1986 for their greatest hits compilation ''[[Made in U.S.A. (The Beach Boys album)|Made in U.S.A.]]''. It was produced by [[Terry Melcher]] and featured [[Roger McGuinn]] of [[The Byrds]] on [[Twelve-string guitar|12-string guitar]]. [[Denny Doherty]] was on the East coast and declined; [[Cass Elliot]] had died in 1974. This version of the song was referenced in the lyrics of [[the Dead Milkmen]]'s 1988 novelty hit \"Punk Rock Girl\".\n\nAlthough the song only charted at a modest number 57 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], it reached {{Numero|8}} on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|''Billboard Adult'' Contemporary]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|title=AllMusic 'Made in U.S.A' awards|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/made-in-usa-mw0000192935/awards|website=AllMusic}}</ref> and it was supported by a music video that saw heavy rotation on MTV. The video featured the Beach Boys along with John Phillips, Michelle Phillips and Roger McGuinn.\n\n====Personnel====\nCredits sourced from Craig Slowinski and Andrew G. Doe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php/topic,16709.msg414538.html#msg414538|title=quick question..California Dreamin'|website=smileysmile.net}}</ref>\n\n'''The Beach Boys'''\n*[[Carl Wilson]] \u2013 Lead Guitar, Lead vocals\n*[[Al Jardine]] \u2013 Rhythm Guitar, Acoustic Guitar, Lead vocals\n*[[Mike Love]] \u2013 Tambourine, vocals\n*[[Brian Wilson]] \u2013 Piano, vocals\n*[[Bruce Johnston]] \u2013 Electric Piano, vocals\n;Additional musicians and production staff\n*[[Roger McGuinn]] \u2013 12-string lead guitar\n*[[Jeff Foskett]] \u2013 Rhythm Guitar, Bass Guitar, possible vocals\n*[[Adrian Baker]] \u2013 possible vocals\n* Bobby Figueroa  \u2013 Drums\n*[[Mike Kowalski]]- Percussion, Drums \n* Ed Carter- Bass Guitar \n* [[Mike Meros]]- Organ, Keyboards, Synthesizer \n*[[Billy Hinsche]]- Bass Guitar, Rhythm Guitar, Vocals\n\n===Freischwimmer version===\nA tropical house version by German DJ/remixer [[Freischwimmer]] was released in 2015. This version reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart in its February 13, 2016 issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/dance-club-play-songs/2016-02-13|title=Dance Songs: Top Dance Music Chart|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/6807308/freischwimmer/chart Chart history for Freischwimmer] from ''Billboard''</ref> \"Dreamin\" had never before hit No. 1 on any ranking, making this version the first in its nearly 50-year history to reach the top spot on a ''Billboard'' chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6866868/california-dreamin-hits-no-1-dance-dj-freischwimmer \"'California Dreamin' Hits No. 1 After 50 Years, Thanks to Dance Remix\"] from ''Billboard'' (February 4, 2016)</ref>\n\n===Lesser-known versions===\n[[Bobby Womack]] recorded a version of the song for his debut album ''[[Fly Me to the Moon (Bobby Womack album)|Fly Me to the Moon]]'' in 1968. Released as a single on [[Minit Records]], the 1968 [[Jose Feliciano]] arrangement reached number 43 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and number 20 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Rhythm & Blues Singles]] chart.\n\nThe elaborate string version of \"California Dreamin'\" by [[Jose Feliciano]] serves as the opening track on his 1968 album ''[[Feliciano!]]'', and it was heard in a key sequence in Quentin Tarantino's 2019 film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''.\n\nIn 1978, a disco version proved popular in European clubs for the Italian project [[Colorado (band)|Colorado]], reaching 45 on the British charts,<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado (2): California Dreaming/Space Lady Love|url=http://www.discogs.com/Colorado-California-Dreaming-Space-Lady-Love/master/236947|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/colorado/|publisher=The Official Charts Company|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref>  and house cover versions have been released by [[DJ Sammy]] and [[Royal Gigolos]].\n\nThe [[Liverpool]] folk quartet [[River City People]] recorded a version of \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-sided single]] with \"Carry the Blame\" in 1990, reaching number 13 on the official UK top 40 singles chart. The single also charted in Ireland, at number 16.\n\nIn 2004, German punk techno group, [[Royal Gigolos]], sampled the song on a track by the same name on their ''Musique Deluxe'' album. The song reached number 2 on the French charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/search.asp?search=royal+gigolos&cat=s |title=French Charts |publisher=lescharts.com |accessdate=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Sia Furler|Sia]] recorded the song for the [[disaster film]] ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''. The song came out in May 2015 and was featured in the movie's trailers. The song reached the top 20 in Lebanon, peaking at {{Numero|14}} and becoming a big airplay gainer there, position no. 92 on the [[UK Singles Chart|''UK'' Singles Chart]], {{Numero|44}} on the [[Official Charts Company|''Scottish'' Singles Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia {{!}} The Official Charts Company|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/9062/SIA/|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> {{Numero|87}} on the chart \n[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|''SNEP'' Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lescharts.com \u2013 Sia \u2013 California Dreamin'|url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=California+Dreamin%27&cat=s|website=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|Les classement single]]|accessdate=25 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2016 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the song, which is allowed under Wikipedia policies, even though it's hosted by MySpace.com -->\n* [https://www.myspace.com/themamasandthepapas/music/songs/california-dreamin-14748 ''California Dreamin'''] at [[Myspace]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110218014724/http://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html NPR's \"Present at the Creation\" segment on the origins of the song]\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204034801/http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ Technical article describing how California Dreamin' was originally mixed]\n\n*[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2016 Facts and discussion about the song]\n\n*[https://archive.org/details/TheStoryOfCaliforniaDreaming_597/ Review Of California Dreaming]\n<!--for The Mamas & the Papas-->\n\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-mamas-the-papas|california-dreamin}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0U8XWyHaGkI |title=California Dreamin', Jazz version performed by Diana Krall |website=YouTube.com}}\n\n{{The Mamas & the Papas}}{{Bobby Womack}}{{The Beach Boys singles}}\n{{Sia singles}}\n\n[[Category:1965 singles]]\n[[Category:1979 singles]]\n[[Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Phillips (musician)]]\n[[Category:The Mamas & the Papas songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Womack songs]]\n[[Category:The Lettermen songs]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters songs]]\n[[Category:America (band) songs]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Sia (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Lou Adler]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Songs about California]]\n[[Category:Songs about Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Hippie movement]]\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Dunhill Records singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor singles]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:1968 singles]]\n[[Category:Minit Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|California Dreaming||California Dreamin' (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      = Disco de vinilo - California dreamin'.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Mamas and the Papas]]\n| album      = [[If You Can Believe Your Eyes and Ears]]\n| B-side     = Somebody Groovy\n| released   = December 8, 1965\n| format     = [[Phonograph record|Vinyl record]] (7\") 45 RPM\n| recorded   = November 4, 1965, Western Recorders, Hollywood\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Sunshine pop]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Dictionnaire des Musiciens: (Les Dictionnaires d'Universalis)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9yKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT3635|date=October 27, 2015|publisher=Encyclopaedia Universalis|isbn=978-2-85229-140-9|page=3635}}</ref>|[[folk rock]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-folk-rock-music-2521910|title= What is Folk-Rock Music?|last= Fontenot|first= Robert|date= October 29, 2015|website= ThoughtCo.|publisher= [[About.com]]|access-date= March 12, 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=38}}\n| label      = [[Dunhill Records]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phillips]]\n| producer   = [[Lou Adler]]\n| prev_title = [[Go Where You Wanna Go]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Monday, Monday]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       =\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=California Dreamin.ogg\n|title=\"California Dreamin'\"\n|description=[[The Mamas and the Papas]]' \"California Dreamin'\" from their debut album, ''[[If You Can Believe Your Eyes and Ears]]''.\n|filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n\"'''California Dreamin'''<nowiki/>'\" is a song written by [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]] and [[Michelle Phillips]] and was first recorded by [[Barry McGuire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/take-two/2013/03/05/30786/how-the-iconic-tune-california-dreamin-came-to-be/|title=Take Two|author=Southern California Public Radio|work=Southern California Public Radio}}</ref> However, the best-known version is by [[the Mamas and the Papas]], who sang backup on the original version and released it as a single in 1965. The song is No. 89 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'s}} list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/the-mamas-and-the-papas-california-dreamin-20110526 |title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416005906/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11028260/the_rs_500_greatest_songs_of_all_time/1 |archivedate=April 16, 2007 |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> The lyrics of the song express the narrator's longing for the warmth of [[Los Angeles]] during a cold winter in [[New York City]].\n\nThe song became a signpost of the [[California Sound]],<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bisbort|first1=Alan|last2=Puterbaugh|first2=Parke|title=California Beaches: The Best Places to Swim, Play, Eat, and Stay|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5D-egP4JWsEC&pg=PA172|year=2009|publisher=Avalon Travel|isbn=978-1-56691-614-1|p=172}}</ref> heralding the arrival of the nascent [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/eagles-fleetwood-mac-selected-for-hall-of-fame-19971028 |title=Eagles, Fleetwood Mac Selected for Hall of Fame &#124; Music News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=1997-10-28 |accessdate=2014-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1146306 |title='California Dreamin,' Present at the Creation (Archived Radio Program) |last=Stamberg|first=Susan|date=2002-07-08 |website=NPR.org |publisher=NPR |accessdate=2014-04-29}}</ref>\n\n\"California Dreamin'\" was certified as a [[Gold Record]] (single) by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] in June 1966<ref>{{cite web|title=California Dreamin'|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|website=RIAA.com|publisher=The Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=2014-07-11|quote=The RIAA Database may require user input}}</ref> and was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=California Dreamin'|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#c|website=grammy.org|publisher=The Recording Academy|accessdate=2014-07-11|quote=CALIFORNIA DREAMIN' The Mamas And The Papas Dunhill (1966) (Single) Inducted 2001}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe song was written in 1963 while [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]] and [[Michelle Phillips]] were living in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottmckenzie.info/interview-5.html|title=1995 Interview (5) - \"California Dreaming\" - Scott McKenzie|website=www.scottmckenzie.info}}</ref> He dreamed about the song and woke her up to help him write it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribut.clothing/monday-night-blues/ep61/ |title=TRIBUT Presents: Monday Night Blues|work=Monday Night Blues}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2016|title=California Dreamin' by The Mamas & the Papas Songfacts|publisher=}}</ref> At the time, John and Michelle Phillips were members of the folk group the New Journeymen, which evolved into [[the Mamas and the Papas]].\n\nThey earned their first record contract after being introduced to [[Lou Adler]], the head of [[Dunhill Records]], by [[Barry McGuire]]. In thanks to Adler, they sang the backing vocals to \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} with members of the session band [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|The Wrecking Crew]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Kent |last=Hartman |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749/page/261 261\u2013263] |year=2012 |title=The Wrecking Crew |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312619749 |url-access=registration |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press|St. Martin's Griffin]] |isbn=978-1-250-03046-7}}</ref> on McGuire's album ''This Precious Time''. The Mamas and the Papas then recorded their own version using the same instrumental and backing vocal tracks, to which they added new vocals<ref name=\"pc33\">{{cite web |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19792/m1/ |title=Show 33 - Revolt of the Fat Angel: American musicians respond to the British invaders. [Part 1] |work=The University of North Texas Digital Library |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref> and an [[alto flute]] solo by [[Bud Shank]]. The guitar introduction was performed by [[P. F. Sloan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ |title=Classic Tracks: The Mamas & The Papas' \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} |last=Daily |first=Dan |date=July 1, 2004 |publisher=Mix Magazine |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204034801/http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ |archivedate=February 4, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> McGuire's original vocal can be briefly heard on the left channel at the beginning of the record, having not been completely erased.<ref>[[Pete Frame|Rock Family Trees]], [[BBC]], interview with McGuire, 1999. McGuire's original harmonica solo can also just be made out under the flute solo.</ref>\n\nThe single was released in late 1965 but was not an immediate breakthrough. After gaining little attention in Los Angeles upon its release, a radio station in Boston was the catalyst to break the song nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html |title=California Dreamin' |work=npr.org |date=July 8, 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218014724/http://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html |archivedate=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 6, 2012}}</ref> After making its chart debut in January 1966,<ref name=\"Sullivan2013\">{{cite book|last=Sullivan|first=Steve|title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA483|date=4 October 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8296-6|pages=483\u2013}}</ref> the song peaked at No. 4 in March on both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], lasting 17 weeks, and ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'', lasting 20 weeks.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bronson|first1=Fred|title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits|date=1988|publisher=Billboard Publications, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-7545-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofnbro00bron/page/195 195]|edition=Paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/billboardbookofnbro00bron/page/195}}</ref> California Dreamin{{'}} also reached number 23 on the UK charts upon its original release, and re-charted after its use in a [[Carling O'Keefe|Carling Premier]] commercial in 1997, peaking at number nine there.<ref>{{cite book| first=Hamish| last=Pringle| title=Celebrity Sells| year=2004| publisher=John Wiley & Sons Ltd| location=Chichester UK| page=[https://archive.org/details/celebritysells00hami/page/36 36]| isbn=0-470-86850-3| url=https://archive.org/details/celebritysells00hami/page/36}}</ref>\n\nThe song is repeatedly used in the 1994 [[Hong Kong]] film ''[[Chungking Express]]'' as a central plot point.<ref>[https://film.avclub.com/song-and-vision-no-5-california-dreamin-and-chungki-1798217949 Song And Vision No. 5: &quot;California Dreamin&#39;&quot; and Chungking Express], Steven Hyden</ref>\n\nMichelle Phillips wrote the lyrics, \"Well, I got down on my knees, and I pretend to pray,\" but Cass Elliot had been singing \"I began to pray\" until corrected by Phillips when they were touring. She sang \"began\" on the original recording.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZVay1RYazI</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n===America version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[America (band)|America]]\n| album      = <br> [[California Dreaming (1979 film)|California Dreaming]] soundtrack\n| B-side     = \"See It My Way\" (by F.D.R.)\n| released   = March 1979\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = Studio 55 (Hollywood) 1978\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[soft rock]]\n| length     = 2:44\n| label      = [[American International Pictures|American International]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phillips]]\n| producer   = [[Dewey Bunnell]], [[Gerry Beckley]]\n| prev_title = Don't Cry Baby\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = Only Game in Town\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\nIn the spring of 1979 the band [[America (band)|America]] reached {{Numero|56}}  on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] with their remake of \"California Dreamin'\" which was the first studio recording by America as the duo of [[Gerry Beckley]] and [[Dewey Bunnell]] without third founding member [[Dan Peek]], who had departed the group in 1977. Bunnell \u2013 who sang lead \u2013 and Beckley \u2013 who sang background \u2013 self-produced the track which featured America's touring musicians: David Dickey, drummer Willie Leacox, guitarist Michael Woods, percussionist Tom Walsh, and Jim Calire who played keyboards and also saxophone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labibledelawestcoast.blogspot.ca/2016/11/|title=La Bible de la Westcoast Music - Cool Night -|website=labibledelawestcoast.blogspot.ca}}</ref><ref name=\"Access Backstage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accessbackstage.com/america/song/song157.htm|title=Lyrics: California Dreamin'|website=www.accessbackstage.com}}</ref>\n\nAmerica had performed \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} at least on occasion in concert as early as 1974,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.setlist.fm/stats/songs/the-mamas-and-the-papas-bd6053e.html?song=California+Dreamin'|title=California Dreamin' by The Mamas & the Papas Song Statistics - setlist.fm|website=www.setlist.fm}}</ref> \"California Dreamin'\" being a sentimental favorite of the band's members having been a setlist staple of the [[cover band]] in which all three had performed while [[London Central Elementary High School|London Central High School]] students in the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite book|title=An American Band: the America Story|last=Peak|first=Dan|year=2004 |publisher=Xulon Press|isbn=1-594679-29-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theslateonline.com/article/2018/02/eeoz41m20k5nn0i|title=Fans brave winter weather for America performance|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/america-brings-sounds-of-summer-to-casino-show-1.1725657|title=America brings sounds of summer to casino show|first=Kristen|last=Gaydos|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucaecho.net/news/america-performs-hit-a-horse-with-no-name/|title=America Performs Hit 'A Horse With No Name'|date=November 14, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The recording of \"California Dreamin'\" by America was specifically made to play under the closing credits of the [[American International Pictures]] (AIP) movie release ''[[California Dreaming (1979 film)|California Dreaming]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornsection.blogspot.com/2011/08/film-review-california-dreaming-1979.html|title=The Horn Section: Film Review: CALIFORNIA DREAMING (1979)|first=Hal|last=Horn|date=August 24, 2011|publisher=}}</ref>  which had been shot in the final months of 1977 for release in the summer of 1978 although the movie would in fact be held back from wide release until 16 March 1979<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56231|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref> with America recording the song \"California Dreamin'\" in the autumn of 1978:<ref name=\"Shirlebrities\">''Detroit Free Press'' \"Shirlebreties\" by Shirley Eder 30 November 1978 p.17B</ref> Beckley and Bunnell agreed to record the song after being (at least partially) shown the movie \u2013 <small>(Gerry Beckley quote:)</small> \"We liked what we saw\"<ref name=\"Access Backstage\"/> \u2013 and the track was recorded at Studio 55 (Hollywood): <small>(Gerry Beckley quote:)</small>\"We did it more as a rock thing [compared to the original], [with] a full sound but reliant on the harmonies.\"<ref name=\"Access Backstage\"/>\n\nThe track was originally scheduled for a 15 January 1979 release<ref name=\"Shirlebrities\"/> which was delayed until after AIP's February 1979 pacting with [[Casablanca Records]] to distribute the  ''California Dreaming'' soundtrack, Casablanca having recently managed to bolster the modest success of the film ''[[Thank God It's Friday (film)|Thank God It's Friday]]'' through a hit soundtrack album:<ref>''Billboard'' Vol 91 #9 (3 Mar 1979) \"Soundtrack lp for Casablanca\" p. 19</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Harris| first=Larry| title=And Party Every Day: the inside story of Casablanca Records| year=2009| publisher=Backbeat Books| location=Milwaukee WI| isbn=9781617133831}}</ref> the recording of \"California Dreamin'\" by America was therefore given parallel release with the movie, another soundtrack item: \"See It My Way\" by session group F.D.R., serving as [[A-side and B-side#B-side|B-side]]. Both the America single and (in April 1978) the soundtrack album were issued by AIP on its own label (distributed by Casablanca): outside the US and Canada, Casablanca acted as label of release.\n \nBy the spring of 1979 America were involved in sessions for their [[Capitol Records]] debut album ''[[Silent Letter (album)|Silent Letter]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessbackstage.com/america/hist04.htm|title=Comprehensive History: America Revisited - Part 4|website=www.accessbackstage.com}}</ref> and were either unable or uninterested in promoting their version of \"California Dreamin'\" which single proved unable to buoy its parent film's faltering box office take. However the publicity inherent in the film's release was evidently enough to afford minor hit status to America's soundtrack item (heard in the film's trailer, America's \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} was also cited in the movie's poster), and despite its lowly chart peak America's \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} remake would be more successful than any of their first five Capitol single releases none of which ranked in the Hot 100 (the band's sixth Capitol single release: \"[[You Can Do Magic (song)|You Can Do Magic]]\", would in 1982 afford the band a sole latterday Top Ten hit).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicvf.com/America.art|title=America Songs \u2022\u2022\u2022 Top Songs / Chart Singles Discography \u2022\u2022\u2022 Music VF, US & UK hits charts|website=www.musicvf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/artist/america|title=America Discography - USA - 45cat|website=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n\n\"California Dreamin{{'\"}} continued to be featured in America's live gigs eventually being established as a mandatory America concert title.<ref>http://www.conncerts.com/americareview.html</ref> A live performance of the song by America is featured on ''[[In Concert (1995 America album)|In Concert]]'' the band's 1996 album release of a 1982 live gig.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/king-biscuit-flower-hour-mw0000178321|title=King Biscuit Flower Hour - America - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref> The band's 1978 recording has been included on the 2000 America retrospective box set ''[[Highway (America album)|Highway: 30 Years Of America]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/highway-30-years-of-america-mw0000086640|title=Highway: 30 Years of America - America - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref> also being featured in 2001 on ''[[The Complete Greatest Hits (America album)|The Complete Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/america-mn0000019297|title=America - Biography, Albums, Streaming Links - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n===Beach Boys version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = California Dreamin'\n| cover      = California_Dreamin'_Beach_Boys.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Beach Boys]]\n| album      = [[Made in U.S.A. (The Beach Boys album)|Made in U.S.A.]]\n| B-side     = [[Lady Lynda|Lady Liberty]]\n| released   = 1986\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = May 1986\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 3:10\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[John Phillips (musician)|John Phillips]], [[Michelle Phillips]]\n| producer   = [[Terry Melcher]]\n| prev_title = [[Rock 'n' Roll to the Rescue]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = Happy Endings\n| next_year  = 1987\n}}\n\n====Background====\nThe Beach Boys recorded \"California Dreamin'\" in 1986 for their greatest hits compilation ''[[Made in U.S.A. (The Beach Boys album)|Made in U.S.A.]]''. It was produced by [[Terry Melcher]] and featured [[Roger McGuinn]] of [[The Byrds]] on [[Twelve-string guitar|12-string guitar]]. [[Denny Doherty]] was on the East coast and declined; [[Cass Elliot]] had died in 1974. This version of the song was referenced in the lyrics of [[the Dead Milkmen]]'s 1988 novelty hit \"Punk Rock Girl\".\n\nAlthough the song only charted at a modest number 57 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], it reached {{Numero|8}} on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|''Billboard Adult'' Contemporary]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|title=AllMusic 'Made in U.S.A' awards|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/made-in-usa-mw0000192935/awards|website=AllMusic}}</ref> and it was supported by a music video that saw heavy rotation on MTV. The video featured the Beach Boys along with John Phillips, Michelle Phillips and Roger McGuinn.\n\n====Personnel====\nCredits sourced from Craig Slowinski and Andrew G. Doe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php/topic,16709.msg414538.html#msg414538|title=quick question..California Dreamin'|website=smileysmile.net}}</ref>\n\n'''The Beach Boys'''\n*[[Carl Wilson]] \u2013 Lead Guitar, Lead vocals\n*[[Al Jardine]] \u2013 Rhythm Guitar, Acoustic Guitar, Lead vocals\n*[[Mike Love]] \u2013 Tambourine, vocals\n*[[Brian Wilson]] \u2013 Piano, vocals\n*[[Bruce Johnston]] \u2013 Electric Piano, vocals\n;Additional musicians and production staff\n*[[Roger McGuinn]] \u2013 12-string lead guitar\n*[[Jeff Foskett]] \u2013 Rhythm Guitar, Bass Guitar, possible vocals\n*[[Adrian Baker]] \u2013 possible vocals\n* Bobby Figueroa  \u2013 Drums\n*[[Mike Kowalski]]- Percussion, Drums \n* Ed Carter- Bass Guitar \n* [[Mike Meros]]- Organ, Keyboards, Synthesizer \n*[[Billy Hinsche]]- Bass Guitar, Rhythm Guitar, Vocals\n\n===Freischwimmer version===\nA tropical house version by German DJ/remixer [[Freischwimmer]] was released in 2015. This version reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart in its February 13, 2016 issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/dance-club-play-songs/2016-02-13|title=Dance Songs: Top Dance Music Chart|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/6807308/freischwimmer/chart Chart history for Freischwimmer] from ''Billboard''</ref> \"Dreamin\" had never before hit No. 1 on any ranking, making this version the first in its nearly 50-year history to reach the top spot on a ''Billboard'' chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6866868/california-dreamin-hits-no-1-dance-dj-freischwimmer \"'California Dreamin' Hits No. 1 After 50 Years, Thanks to Dance Remix\"] from ''Billboard'' (February 4, 2016)</ref>\n\n===Lesser-known versions===\n[[Bobby Womack]] recorded a version of the song for his debut album ''[[Fly Me to the Moon (Bobby Womack album)|Fly Me to the Moon]]'' in 1968. Released as a single on [[Minit Records]], the 1968 [[Jose Feliciano]] arrangement reached number 43 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and number 20 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Rhythm & Blues Singles]] chart.\n\nThe elaborate string version of \"California Dreamin'\" by [[Jose Feliciano]] serves as the opening track on his 1968 album ''[[Feliciano!]]'', and it was heard in a key sequence in Quentin Tarantino's 2019 film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''.\n\nIn 1978, a disco version proved popular in European clubs for the Italian project [[Colorado (band)|Colorado]], reaching 45 on the British charts,<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado (2): California Dreaming/Space Lady Love|url=http://www.discogs.com/Colorado-California-Dreaming-Space-Lady-Love/master/236947|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/colorado/|publisher=The Official Charts Company|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref>  and house cover versions have been released by [[DJ Sammy]] and [[Royal Gigolos]].\n\nThe [[Liverpool]] folk quartet [[River City People]] recorded a version of \"California Dreamin{{'\"}} as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-sided single]] with \"Carry the Blame\" in 1990, reaching number 13 on the official UK top 40 singles chart. The single also charted in Ireland, at number 16.\n\nIn 2004, German punk techno group, [[Royal Gigolos]], sampled the song on a track by the same name on their ''Musique Deluxe'' album. The song reached number 2 on the French charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/search.asp?search=royal+gigolos&cat=s |title=French Charts |publisher=lescharts.com |accessdate=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Sia Furler|Sia]] recorded the song for the [[disaster film]] ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''. The song came out in May 2015 and was featured in the movie's trailers. The song reached the top 20 in Lebanon, peaking at {{Numero|14}} and becoming a big airplay gainer there, position no. 92 on the [[UK Singles Chart|''UK'' Singles Chart]], {{Numero|44}} on the [[Official Charts Company|''Scottish'' Singles Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia {{!}} The Official Charts Company|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/9062/SIA/|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> {{Numero|87}} on the chart \n[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|''SNEP'' Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lescharts.com \u2013 Sia \u2013 California Dreamin'|url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=California+Dreamin%27&cat=s|website=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|Les classement single]]|accessdate=25 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2016 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the song, which is allowed under Wikipedia policies, even though it's hosted by MySpace.com -->\n* [https://www.myspace.com/themamasandthepapas/music/songs/california-dreamin-14748 ''California Dreamin'''] at [[Myspace]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110218014724/http://www.npr.org/programs/morning/features/patc/californiadreamin/index.html NPR's \"Present at the Creation\" segment on the origins of the song]\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204034801/http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_mamas_papas_california/ Technical article describing how California Dreamin' was originally mixed]\n\n*[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2016 Facts and discussion about the song]\n\n*[https://archive.org/details/TheStoryOfCaliforniaDreaming_597/ Review Of California Dreaming]\n<!--for The Mamas & the Papas-->\n\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-mamas-the-papas|california-dreamin}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0U8XWyHaGkI |title=California Dreamin', Jazz version performed by Diana Krall |website=YouTube.com}}\n\n{{The Mamas & the Papas}}{{Bobby Womack}}{{The Beach Boys singles}}\n{{Sia singles}}\n\n[[Category:1965 singles]]\n[[Category:1979 singles]]\n[[Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Phillips (musician)]]\n[[Category:The Mamas & the Papas songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Womack songs]]\n[[Category:The Lettermen songs]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters songs]]\n[[Category:America (band) songs]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Sia (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Lou Adler]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Songs about California]]\n[[Category:Songs about Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Hippie movement]]\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Dunhill Records singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor singles]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:1968 singles]]\n[[Category:Minit Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "76.97.88.235", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAmerica version)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_Dreamin%27"}
