st to 11,000 career receiving yards (115 games)\n* Fastest to 12,000 career receiving yards (125 games)\n* Consecutive seasons with 1,400+ yards receiving (5)\n* Consecutive seasons with 1,500+ yards receiving (2, tied with [[Marvin Harrison]], [[Andre Johnson]], [[Calvin Johnson]], and [[Antonio Brown]])\n* Fewest games to record 500 career receptions (80, tied with [[Anquan Boldin]])\n* Most 100+ yard games in his first 8 seasons (52)\n* Most receiving yards in first 100 games: 9,618\n* Most receiving yards per game average, career: 96.7\n* Most receiving yards in a single game against the [[Carolina Panthers]] (300)\n* Most receiving yards in a single game against the [[Green Bay Packers]] (259)\n* Most receiving yards in a single game against the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (253)\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Falcons franchise records===\n* Most career receiving yards: 12,125\n* Most career 100+ receiving yard games: 58 (55 regular-season, 3 post-season)\n* Most seasons with 1,000+ receiving yards (7)\n* Most receiving yards in a single game: 300 (2016)\n* Most receptions in a single season: 136 (2015)\n* Most receiving yards in a single season: 1,871 (2015)\n* Most 100+ receiving yard games in a single season: 10 (2018)\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] selections ([[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2015 All-Pro Team|2015]], [[2016 All-Pro Team|2016]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]], [[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]], [[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of National Football League season receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (2015, 2018)\n* [[List of NFL annual receptions leaders|NFL receptions co-leader]] (2015)\n* [[National Football Conference|NFC]] Offensive Player of the Month (September 2015)\n* 2008 [[Associated Press|AP]] [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] Freshman of the Year<ref name=\"2008-AP-Awards\"/>\n* ''[[Sporting News]]'' SEC Freshman of the Year (2008)<ref name=\"montgomeryadvertiser.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20081215/NEWS/81215017 |title=Sporting News names Saban SEC Coach of the Year |work=Montgomery Adviser |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=January 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216091008/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20081215/NEWS/81215017 |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n* ''Sporting News'' All-Freshman Team (2008)<ref name=\"sportingnews.com\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/college-football/article/2008-12-16/sporting-news-college-football-all-freshman-team |title=Sporting News' college football All-Freshman Team |date=December 16, 2008 |work=Sporting News |access-date=January 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629102024/http://www.sportingnews.com/college-football/article/2008-12-16/sporting-news-college-football-all-freshman-team |archive-date=June 29, 2009}}</ref>\n* AP Second Team All-SEC (2008)<ref name=\"2008-AP-Awards\" />\n* SEC Coaches' All-Freshman Team (2008)<ref name=\"Freshman-SEC\"/>\n* Preseason All-SEC Coaches Football Team (2009, 2010)\n* Playboy Preseason All-American Team (2009, 2010) <ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/060710aaa.html |title=Ingram, Jones Recognized as Playboy Preseason All-Americans; McElroy Named Anson Mount Scholar-Athlete |work=Alabama Crimson Tide |access-date=October 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617153500/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/060710aaa.html |archive-date=June 17, 2010 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[2009 SEC Championship Game|2009 SEC Championship]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/columns/story?columnist=forde_pat&id=4717584 |title=Gators couldn't solve McElroy |last=Forde |first=Pat |date=December 5, 2009 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[2010 BCS National Championship]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/bowls09/columns/story?columnist=forde_pat&id=4807215 |title=Saban's trademark plays key Bama's win |last=Forde |first=Pat |date=January 7, 2010 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* AP All-SEC Team (2010)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://alabama.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1162068 |title=Associated Press names three Tide players All-SEC |last=Walsh |first=Christopher |date=December 6, 2010 |work=BamaOnline.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |publisher=Rivals.com}}</ref>\n* Coaches' All-SEC Team (2010)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/12/tide_has_four_first-team_selec.html |title=Tide has four first-team selections on coaches' All-SEC team |last=Kausler Jr. |first=Don |date=December 7, 2010 |work=The Birmingham News |access-date=February 5, 2011 |publisher=AL.com}}</ref>\n* AP All-American Team (2010)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/12/ap_all-american_teams_include.html |title=AP All-American teams include four from Alabama |last=Gould |first=Izzy |date=December 14, 2010 |work=The Birmingham News |access-date=February 5, 2011 |publisher=AL.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Football stats |nfl=2495454 |espn=13982 |pfr=J/JoneJu02 }}\n* [http://www.atlantafalcons.com/team/roster/Julio-Jones/3fa3dd5e-0294-4d80-add9-68e47289bf80 Atlanta Falcons bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605204740/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/jones_julio00.html Alabama Crimson Tide bio]\n* {{Twitter|juliojones_11}}\n\n{{2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2011 NFL Draft}}\n{{FalconsFirstPick}}\n{{Falcons2011DraftPicks}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n{{NFL2010s}}\n{{Atlanta Falcons roster navbox original}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Julio}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:People from Foley, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Under Armour All-American football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Julio Jones\n| image = Julio Jones 2019 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Jones with the Atlanta Falcons in 2019\n| current_team = Atlanta Falcons \n| number = 11\n| position = [[Wide receiver]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|2|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Foley, Alabama]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 220\n| high_school = [[Foley High School|Foley]] ([[Foley, Alabama]])\n| college = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| draftyear = 2011\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 6\n| pastteams = \n* [[Atlanta Falcons ]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013present)\n| status = Active\n| highlights = \n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]]) \n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2015 All-Pro Team|2015]], [[2016 All-Pro Team|2016]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]], [[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]], [[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of National Football League season receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (2015, 2018)\n* [[List of NFL annual receptions leaders|NFL receptions co-leader]] (2015)\n* [[National Football League 2010s All-Decade Team|NFL 2010s All-Decade Team]]\n* [[BCS National Championship Game|BCS national champion]] ([[2010 BCS National Championship|2009]])\n* [[SEC Championship Game|SEC champion]] ([[2009 SEC Championship Game|2009]])\n* [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards#Freshman of the Year|SEC Freshman of the Year]] (2008)\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2010 All-SEC football team|2010]])\n* Second-team All-SEC ([[2008 All-SEC football team|2008]])\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2007 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2007]])\n* NFL record 96.2 average receiving yards per game<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_per_g_career.htm |title=NFL Receiving Yards per Game Career Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| statweek   = 17\n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Reception (gridiron football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1 = 797\n| statlabel2 = [[Receiving yards]]\n| statvalue2 = 12,125\n| statlabel3= Yards per reception\n| statvalue3 = 15.2\n| statlabel4 = [[Touchdown|Receiving touchdown]]s\n| statvalue4 = 57\n| nfl-new = juliojones/2495454\n}}\n\n'''Quintorris Lopez''' \"'''Julio'''\" '''Jones'''<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blog.al.com/bamabeat/2009/11/who_exactly_is_crimson_tide_st.html |title=Who exactly is Crimson Tide Star Julio Jones? |last=Estes |first=Gentry |date=November 1, 2009 |work=Mobile-Press Register |access-date=August 2, 2012 |publisher=AL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://recruiting.scout.com/2/699436.html |title=The Race for Number One: Julio Jones |last=Safrit |first=Miller |date=November 8, 2007 |access-date=August 2, 2012 |publisher=Scout.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026005547/http://recruiting.scout.com/2/699436.html |archive-date=October 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0|l|i|o\u028a}}; born February 8, 1989)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/juliojones/2495454/profile | title=Julio Jones \u2013 Atlanta Falcons \u2013 2017 Player Profile | publisher=NFL.com | accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref> is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], and in 2009, helped lead the Crimson Tide to an undefeated 14\u20130 season, including a victory in the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game]]. \n\nJones was drafted by the [[Atlanta Falcons]] sixth overall in the [[2011 NFL Draft]]. With the Falcons, Jones has been invited to seven [[Pro Bowl]]s, was a first-team [[All-Pro]] selection in 2015 after leading the league in receiving yards and receptions, and in 2016 when he helped lead the Falcons to [[Super Bowl LI]]. Jones was also named second-team [[All-Pro]] three times, in 2017, in 2018 after leading the league in receiving yards, and in 2019. Since entering the league, Jones has amassed more receiving yards than any other player.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/HlGDi |title=NFL career receiving yards since the 2011 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref> \n\nJones has a rare combination of size (6&nbsp;ft 3 in and 220&nbsp;lbs), speed ([[40-yard dash]] in 4.39 seconds), catching ability, strength, leaping ability, and body control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/julio-jones?id=2495454|title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles \u2013 Julio Jones|website=www.nfl.com|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> On November 11, 2018, Jones became the fastest player in NFL history to reach 10,000 career receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/atlanta-falcons/post/_/id/33343 |title=Julio Jones becomes fastest receiver to 10,000 yards |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=November 11, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> On September 15, 2019, Jones became the all-time career receiving yards leader for the Falcons.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Unleashing Your Inner Leader |date=February 3, 2015 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |isbn=9781118936689 |pages=137\u2013162 |chapter=Career Evolution: Where Are You Going? |doi=10.1002/9781118936689.ch9}}</ref> His career average of 96.2 receiving yards per game is the highest in NFL history.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL Receiving Yards per Game Career Leaders|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_per_g_career.htm|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nJones attended [[Foley High School]] in [[Foley, Alabama]], where he played wide receiver and [[defensive end]] for the Lions [[high school football]] team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.juliojones.com/pages/julio-jones-bio |title=Julio Jones Bio |website=JulioJones.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809211757/https://www.juliojones.com/pages/julio-jones-bio |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> During his high school career, Jones quickly achieved recognition from outstanding statistics. In his junior year, he caught 75 passes for 1,306 yards and had 16 [[touchdown]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/2016/6/3/16045630/julio-jones-atlanta-falcons-3fa47fb03461 |title=The NFL's Chosen One |last=Mays |first=Robert |date=June 3, 2016 |website=The Ringer |access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> He participated in the High School [[Under Armour All-America Game]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/sec/under-armour-best-wide-receivers-julio-jones-a-j-green-amari-cooper |title=Best Under Armour All-America Game wide receivers of all time |last=Capps |first=Randy |website=SEC Country |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809212913/https://www.seccountry.com/sec/under-armour-best-wide-receivers-julio-jones-a-j-green-amari-cooper |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> and ran a 4.55-second [[40-yard dash]] at the [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] camp in May 2007,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://atsports.com/post/12-moments-in-the-making-of-the-dominant-julio-jones/ |title=12 Moments In The Making Of The Dominant Julio Jones |publisher=At Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013932/http://atsports.com/post/12-moments-in-the-making-of-the-dominant-julio-jones/ |archive-date=August 10, 2017 |access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> where he also recorded an event-best {{convert|38.6|in|adj=on}} vertical jump.\n\nIn addition to football, Jones was a starter on the [[high school basketball|basketball]] team and was a standout [[track and field|track]] athlete. He was the state champion in the [[long jump]] (24\u20132 or 7.40m) and [[triple jump]] (47\u20135 or 14.52m) in both 2006 and 2007. He was named the 2006\u201307 [[Gatorade Player of the Year awards|Gatorade T&F Athlete of the Year]] in the state of [[Alabama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gatorade.com/poy/winner/state|title=Gatorade State High School Players of the Year|website=www.gatorade.com|access-date=April 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509204255/http://www.gatorade.com/poy/winner/state|archive-date=May 9, 2017|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> He was the state champion in the [[high jump]] (6\u20136 or 1.98m) during the 2007 indoor season. He was named All-county selection in 2005, 2006, and 2007. He won Mr. Alabama Track & Field athlete of the year in 2007. He also competed as a [[sprint (running)|sprinter]] in 2008, and posted a personal-best time of 11.13 seconds in the [[100-meter dash]] at the Class 6A Section 1 Meet, where he placed second.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://al.milesplit.com/meets/35931-class-6a-section-1/results/66381/raw |title=Class 6A - Section 1 - Complete Results (Raw) |website=AlabamaRunners |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConsidered a five-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rivals.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Julio-Jones-54050;_ylt=At_hPsFpckCszv_LuEheq5FDPZB4 |title=Julio Jones profile |website=Rivals.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110013053/https://rivals.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Julio-Jones-54050;_ylt=At_hPsFpckCszv_LuEheq5FDPZB4 |archive-date=January 10, 2015}}</ref> Jones was listed as the No. 1 wide receiver in the nation in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-1823/0 |title=Recruiting Rankings |website=Yahoo! Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111192731/https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-1823/0 |archive-date=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2008, Jones committed to the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]] on [[National Signing Day]], announcing his decision live on [[ESPNU]].<ref name=\"Jones-commit\">{{Cite web |url=http://rivals100.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=880&CID=770342 |title=Jones chooses UA |last=Watts |first=Tim |date=February 6, 2008 |website=Rivals.com |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n===2008 season===\nIn the first of three years on the Crimson Tide, Jones quickly became an impact player and a fan favorite under head coach [[Nick Saban]]. Jones became the first [[true freshman]] wide receiver to start in a season opener for the Crimson Tide,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.crimsonconfidential.com/news/story.php?article=362 |title=Top freshman receivers rare in Tide history |last=Stephenson |first=Creg |date=August 23, 2008 |website=Crimson Confidential |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> as he started against the [[2008 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson Tigers]] in the 2008 [[Chick-fil-A College Kickoff]]. In the game, Jones caught four passes for 28&nbsp;yards and a touchdown in a 34\u201310 rout.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama01.html| title=Alabama vs Clemson (Aug 30, 2008)| website=University of Alabama Athletics| date=August 30, 2008| accessdate=December 9, 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202154330/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama01.html| archivedate=February 2, 2012| df=}}</ref> In a 41\u201330 win over the #3 ranked [[2008 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]], Jones had a breakout performance as he caught five passes for 94 yards, including a 22-yard touchdown reception from [[John Parker Wilson]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama05.html| title=Alabama vs Georgia (Sep 27, 2008)| website=University of Alabama Athletics| date=September 27, 2008| accessdate=December 9, 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202115704/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama05.html| archivedate=February 2, 2012| df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/092708aaa.html |title=No. 8 Alabama Beats No. 3 Georgia, 41\u201330 |last=Latta |first=Scott |date=September 27, 2008 |website=University of Alabama Athletics |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> His first 100-yard receiving game occurred in [[Third Saturday in October|the annual rivalry game]] versus [[2008 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], as Jones had six receptions for 103&nbsp;yards en route to a 29\u20139 victory.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama08.html| title=Alabama vs Tennessee (Oct 25, 2008)| website=University of Alabama Athletics| date=October 25, 2008| accessdate=December 9, 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202144609/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama08.html| archivedate=February 2, 2012| df=}}</ref> However, two weeks later versus #16 [[2008 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]], Jones topped his previous performance with seven catches for 128&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama10.html| title=Alabama vs LSU (Nov 8, 2008)| website=University of Alabama Athletics| date=November 8, 2008| accessdate=December 9, 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202171103/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama10.html| archivedate=February 2, 2012| df=}}</ref> His 23-yard reception in overtime set up a game-winning touchdown by John Parker Wilson,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=283130099&period=5 |title=Alabama Crimson Tide vs. LSU Tigers Play-by-Play \u2013 OT |date=November 8, 2008 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> giving Alabama a 27\u201321 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=283130099 |title=Saban makes victorious return to Tiger Stadium as Bama stays unbeaten |date=November 8, 2008 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2008 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the [[2008 SEC Championship Game]], Jones caught five passes for 124&nbsp;yards versus a talented [[2008 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]] secondary.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama13.html| title=Alabama vs Florida (Dec 6, 2008)| website=University of Alabama Athletics| date=December 6, 2008| accessdate=December 9, 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202171648/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/bama13.html| archivedate=February 2, 2012| df=}}</ref> In the first quarter, Jones caught a 64-yard pass which set up the Crimson Tide's first score of the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=283410057 |title=Alabama Crimson Tide vs. Florida Gators Play-by-Play \u2013 1st Qtr |date=December 6, 2008 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> However, #1 Alabama fell to #2 Florida by a score of 31\u201320, giving the Crimson Tide their first loss of the year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ocala.com/article/20081207/News/604247705 |title=Florida beats Alabama, 31-20 |last=Andreu |first=Robbie |date=December 7, 2008 |website=Ocala.com |language=en |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Jones finished his freshman season leading all receivers on the Crimson Tide with 58 receptions for 924 receiving yards and four receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/julio-jones-1/gamelog/2008 |title=Julio Jones 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2008.html |title=2008 Alabama Crimson Tide Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, the Southeastern Conference announced the annual All-SEC first team, second team, and individual awards, as voted by the [[Associated Press]]. Jones was named to the second team All-SEC, SEC Freshman of the Year,<ref name=\"2008-AP-Awards\">{{cite news|url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=11923&change_well_id=2 |title=2008 AP All-SEC Football Team Announced |website=SECSports.com |date=December 8, 2008 |accessdate=January 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216011016/http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=11923&change_well_id=2 |archivedate=December 16, 2008 |df= }}</ref> and the SEC Coaches' All-Freshman Team.<ref name=\"Freshman-SEC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=11940&change_well_id=2 |title=2008 SEC Football All-Freshman Team Announced |website=SECSports.com |date=December 11, 2008 |accessdate=January 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213075653/http://secsports.com/index.php?s= |archivedate=February 13, 2009 }}</ref> Jones finished the regular season with 58 receptions, 924&nbsp;yards, and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/player/profile?playerId=379062 |title=Julio Jones |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> His performance in only his freshman year drew comparisons to NFL greats. [[ESPN.com]] reported, \"This guy is a unique, rare prospect for the wide receiver position with his supreme blend of size, power, speed and agility. He reminds us of a high school version of [[Michael Irvin]], but at this stage Jones is more explosive and faster.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/player?recruitId=46269&season=2008 |title=Julio Jones Rankings, Grade, News, Stats |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2008}}</ref> An NFL scout put Jones in the same category as [[Arizona Cardinals]] receiver [[Larry Fitzgerald]], who at the time was the second-leading receiver in the NFL.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=McCarter |authorlink= |title=Jones' production has matched hype |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?/base/sports/122786732449400.xml&coll=1 |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |publisher= |date=November 28, 2008 |accessdate=February 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609100111/http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fsports%2F122786732449400.xml&coll=1 |archivedate=June 9, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2009 season===\nPreceding the 2009 football season, Jones was voted to the All-SEC Coaches' Football Team (first team), one of only four players to be voted such unanimously along with Florida quarterback [[Tim Tebow]], Tennessee safety [[Eric Berry]], and LSU offensive lineman [[Ciron Black]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=12867&change_well_id=2 |title=SEC Coaches Preseason All-SEC Team Announced |date=July 16, 2009 |website=SECSports.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719082321/http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=12867&change_well_id=2 |archive-date=July 19, 2009 |access-date=July 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Julio Jones, Bama at Arkansas, 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Jones in a game against Arkansas in 2010]]Jones and Alabama again opened their season at the [[Georgia Dome]], this time facing #7 [[2009 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]] for the 2009 [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]]. However, the Crimson Tide's rushing game dominated the game, led by eventual [[Heisman Trophy]] winner and teammate, [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.heisman.com/articles/this-week-in-heisman-history-mark-ingram-comes-up-big-against-lsu/ |title=This Week in Heisman History: Mark Ingram comes up big against LSU |last=Huston |first=Chris |date=November 2, 2018 |website=Heisman |language=en-US |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref> Jones finished the game with four receptions for 46&nbsp;yards,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292480259 |title=Alabama shakes off kick return, turnovers to overcome Virginia Tech |date=September 5, 2009 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> with Alabama winning the game 34\u201324.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=292480259 |title=Alabama shakes off kick return, turnovers to overcome Virginia Tech |date=September 5, 2009 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> His first touchdown of the season would not come until September 26, as the Tide routed the [[2009 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas Razorbacks]] 35\u20137 in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=292690333 |title=Alabama rolls Arkansas as McElroy passes for career-high 291 yards, 3 TDs |date=September 26, 2009 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Jones caught a 50-yard touchdown pass from quarterback [[Greg McElroy]], coming from a trick play, to put Alabama up 14\u20130 midway through the first quarter.<ref name=\"09-arky-stats\">{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292690333 |title=Alabama rolls Arkansas as McElroy passes for career-high 291 yards, 3 TDs |date=September 26, 2009 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He would finish the game with two catches for 65&nbsp;yards.<ref name=\"09-arky-stats\" />\n\nAfter experiencing what some writers called a \"sophomore slump\",<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blog.al.com/tide-source/2010/01/tides_julio_jones_hard_to_beat.html |title=Tide's Julio Jones hard to beat with two good knees |last=Kausler Jr. |first=Don |date=January 5, 2010 |work=The Birmingham News |access-date=February 5, 2011 |publisher=AL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blog.al.com/bamabeat/2010/01/julio_jones_opens_up_about_kne.html |title=Julio Jones' sophomore slump was tied to lingering knee injury |last=Estes |first=Gentry |date=January 4, 2010 |work=Mobile Press-Register |access-date=February 5, 2011 |publisher=AL.com}}</ref> Jones's production increased during the second half of the [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2009 season]]. In a game against #9  [[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rivalry game against LSU]], Jones had his only 100-yard performance of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/player/gamelog?playerId=379062&year=2009 |title=Julio Jones Stats |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref> He finished with four catches for 102&nbsp;yards, including a 73-yard game-winning touchdown in Alabama's 24\u201315 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=293110333 |title=Crimson Tide hold back Tigers for 2nd straight SEC title-game berth |date=November 7, 2009 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=293110333 |title=Crimson Tide hold back Tigers for 2nd straight SEC title-game berth |date=November 7, 2009 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the annual Iron Bowl game against rival [[2009 Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]], Jones was instrumental in capping a come-from-behind victory, catching three crucial third-down passes in an 8-minute, 80-yard drive that fans call \"The Drive\" to set up running back Roy Upchurch's game-winning touchdown in the waning minutes of the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g6JZlE7dp98 |title=2009 Iron Bowl Alabama vs. Auburn - The Championship Drive |date=August 9, 2011 |website=YouTube |others=Crimson Tide Zone |access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlabama continued through the regular season undefeated at 12\u20130, working their way to a [[2009 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]] matchup with the #1 [[2009 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]]. Jones made the first catch of the game, an 18-yard catch from McElroy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=293390333 |title=Florida Gators vs. Alabama Crimson Tide \u2013 Play By Play |date=December 5, 2009 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref> The Crimson Tide won the game 32\u201313,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=293390333 |title=Alabama finishes off Florida for berth in BCS title game |date=December 5, 2009 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> earning a chance to play for the [[BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship]] in the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game|2010 title game]] against the #2 [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas Longhorns]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/topstories/2009-12-05-1322505938_x.htm |title=Alabama rolls, Texas slips into BCS championship |last=Russo |first=Ralph D. |date=December 6, 2009 |work=USA Today |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/dallas/columns/story?columnist=durrett_richard&id=4720896 |title=BCS chooses Alabama Crimson Tide, Texas Longhorns for title game |last=Durrett |first=Richard |date=December 7, 2009 |work=ESPN Dallas |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref> His 23&nbsp;yards receiving led the Tide in the title game, as the passing game struggled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=300070333 |title=Alabama defeats Texas, rolls to first national title since 1992 |date=January 7, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 5, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> However, the running game again took over for 205 total rushing yards and led Alabama to a 37\u201321 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/stewart_mandel/01/08/alabama-texas/index.html |title=Alabama made it tough, but champion Tide know no other way |last=Mandel |first=Stewart |date=January 8, 2010 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/2010-01-07-bcs-title-game_N.htm |title=Alabama sidesteps Texas' charge to emerge with BCS title |last=Whiteside |first=Kelly |date=January 8, 2010 |work=USA Today |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2010 season===\nJones started his junior season with a solid performance against [[2010 San Diego State Aztecs football team|San Diego State]] with six receptions for 93 yards and a touchdown in the 48\u20133 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-09-04-alabama.html |title=San Jose State at Alabama Box Score, September 4, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Two weeks later, Jones had five receptions for 106 yards and a touchdown in a 62\u201313 victory over [[2010 Duke Blue Devils football team|Duke]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-09-18-duke.html |title=Alabama at Duke Box Score, September 18, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On October 9, in a conference game against #19 [[2010 South Carolina Gamecocks football team|South Carolina]], Jones had eight receptions for 118 yards and a touchdown in the Crimson Tide's 35\u201321 loss to the Gamecocks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-10-09-south-carolina.html |title=Alabama at South Carolina Box Score, October 9, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On October 23, Jones torched the [[2010 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee Volunteers]] for 221 yards on 12 receptions, which were good for collegiate career highs in both, in a 41\u201310 victory at [[Neyland Stadium]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-10-23-tennessee.html |title=Alabama at Tennessee Box Score, October 23, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On November 6, Jones had 10 receptions for 89 yards and a touchdown in a 24\u201321 loss to #12 [[2010 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] at [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2010.html |title=2010 Alabama Crimson Tide Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> One week later, Jones was held to only three receptions for 41 yards in a 30\u201310 victory over [[2010 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]] but had a 56-yard rushing touchdown in the victory.<ref name=\"auto\" /> In the following game, against [[2010 Georgia State Panthers football team|Georgia State]], he recorded his first collegiate game with two receiving touchdowns in the 63\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-11-18-alabama.html |title=Georgia State at Alabama Box Score, November 18, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On November 26, in the Iron Bowl against #2 [[2010 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], Jones had ten receptions for 199 yards and a touchdown, but the Crimson Tide lost to the Tigers by a score of 28\u201327.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-11-26-alabama.html |title=Auburn at Alabama Box Score, November 26, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> The Crimson Tide reached a bowl game, which was Jones's final collegiate game. In the [[2011 Capital One Bowl]] against [[2010 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]], Jones had three receptions for 49 yards and 36 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in the 49\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2011-01-01-alabama.html |title=Capital One Bowl \u2013 Michigan State vs Alabama Box Score, January 1, 2011 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones ended his junior season with an Alabama record 78 catches and 1,133 yards along with seven touchdowns (fourth in school history). In addition, he had eight rushes for 135 yards and two touchdowns along with five punt returns for 44 yards and five kickoff returns for 129 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/julio-jones-1/gamelog/2010 |title=Julio Jones 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones ended his Alabama career second in career receptions (179) and yards (2,653) in school history and fourth in touchdown catches (15).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/receiving.html |title=Alabama Crimson Tide Receiving |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He had eight career 100-yard receiving games (second in school history). Jones was a first-team All-SEC selection in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/alabama-football/best-sec-players-last-decade-10-julio-jones/ |title=Best SEC players of the last decade: No. 10 Julio Jones |last=Smith |first=Christopher |website=Saturday Down South |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===College career statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Year !! rowspan=2|GP\u2013GS !! colspan=8|Rushing !! colspan=6|Receiving !! colspan=5|Punt Returns !! colspan=5|Kick Returns\n|-\n ! Att !! Gain !! Loss !! Net !! Avg !! TD !! Long !! Avg/G !! Rec !! Rec\u2013Yards !! Avg !! TD !! Long !! Avg/G !! No. !! Yards !! Avg !! TD !! Long !! No. !! Yards !! Avg !! TD !! Long\n|-\n | [[2008 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2008]]<ref name=\"2008I\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND |title=2008\u201309 Overall Individual Statistics |author=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics |publisher=RollTide.com |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> || 14\u201314\n | 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 58 || 924 || 15.9 || 4 || 64 || 66 || 2 || 11 || 5.5 || 0 || 10 || 1 || 21 || 21 || 0 || 21\n|-\n | [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2009]]<ref name=\"2009I\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2009-2010/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND |title=2009\u201310 Overall Individual Statistics |author=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics |publisher=RollTide.com |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> || 13\u201313\n | 2 || 5 || 1 || 4 || 2 || 0 || 5 || 0.3 || 43 || 596 || 13.9 || 4 || 73 || 45.8 || 5 || 75 || 15 || 0 || 33 || 1 || 12 || 12 || 0 || 12\n|-\n | [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]]<ref name=\"2010I\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2010-2011/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND |title=2010\u201311 Overall Individual Statistics |author=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics |publisher=RollTide.com |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> || 13\u201313\n | 8 || 135 || 0 || 135 || 16.9 || 2 || 56 || 10.4 || 78 || 1,133 || 14.5 || 7 || 68 || 87.2 || 5 || 44 || 8.8 || 0 || 41 || 5 || 129 || 25.8 || 0 || 36\n|-\n ! colspan=2|Total\n ! 10 !! 140 !! 1 !! 139 !! 13.9 !! 2 !! 56 !! 3.5 !! 179 !! 2,653 !! 14.8 !! 15 !! 73 !! 66.3 !! 12 !! 130 !! 10.8 !! 0 !! 41 !! 7 !! 162 !! 23.1 !! 0 !! 36\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:Julio Jones catching a pass.jpg|thumb|Jones playing for the Atlanta Falcons against the Seattle Seahawks in the divisional round of the 2012 NFL playoffs]]\n\nOn January 7, 2011, Jones decided to forego his senior season of college football. Instead, he chose to declare eligibility for the [[2011 NFL Draft|NFL Draft]] with teammates [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]], [[Greg McElroy]], and [[Marcell Dareus]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.baldwincountynow.com/articles/2011/01/10/sports/doc4d2b5c49d88d0814105192.txt |title=Julio Jones headed for NFL |last=Mann |first=Eric |date=January 10, 2010 |work=Baldwin County NOW |access-date=February 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120180740/http://www.baldwincountynow.com/articles/2011/01/10/sports/doc4d2b5c49d88d0814105192.txt |archive-date=January 20, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2011/01/alabama-mark-ingram-julio-jones-marcell-dareus-nfl-draft/1 |title=Ingram, Jones, Dareus all leaving Alabama for NFL |last=Smith |first=Erick |date=January 7, 2011 |work=USA Today |access-date=February 5, 2011}}</ref> Jones was later invited to the \"All-Star Football Challenge\", a skill contest shown by [[ESPN]] on February 4.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2011/01/julio_jones_to_compete_in_13th.html |title=Julio Jones to compete in 13th annual All-Star Football Challenge |last=Gould |first=Izzy |date=January 29, 2011 |website=AL.com |language=en |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> He excelled at the 2011 [[NFL Scouting Combine|NFL Combine]], posting the longest [[long jump]] and the third fastest [[40-yard dash]] among wide receivers,<ref name=\"espn\">{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/20290/one-more-time-green-vs-jones |title=One more time: Green vs. Jones |last=Low |first=Chris |date=February 28, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> despite having a broken bone in his foot.\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2 3/4\n|       weight = 220\n|         dash = 4.39\n|    ten split = \n| twenty split = \n|      shuttle = 4.25\n|   cone drill = 6.66\n|     vertical = 38\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 11\n|     broad in = 3\n|        bench = 17\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 33\u00be\n|    hand span = 9\u00be\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/julio-jones?id=2495454 |title=Julio Jones Combine Profile |work=NFL.com |accessdate=March 1, 2011 }}.</ref>\n}}\n\nThe [[Atlanta Falcons]] selected Jones with the sixth overall pick of the [[2011 NFL Draft]].  Atlanta traded five draft picks to the [[Cleveland Browns]] to move up into their spot and take Jones, giving up their [[Jon Baldwin|27th]], [[Greg Little (wide receiver)|59th]], and [[Owen Marecic|124th]] picks from the [[2011 NFL Draft|2011 Draft]], and their [[Brandon Weeden|first]] and [[Jarius Wright|fourth]] round picks from the [[2012 NFL Draft|2012 Draft]].<ref name=\"AJCApril 28, 2011\">{{cite news | url =http://blogs.ajc.com/jeff-schultz-blog/2011/04/28/falcons-pick-right-time-to-make-big-move-get-julio-jones/ | last =Schultz | first =Jeff | title =Falcons pick right time to make big move, get Julio Jones | work =The Atlanta Journal-Constitution | date =April 28, 2011 | accessdate =April 29, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110502031002/http://blogs.ajc.com/jeff-schultz-blog/2011/04/28/falcons-pick-right-time-to-make-big-move-get-julio-jones/ | archivedate =May 2, 2011 | df = }}</ref> He was the second wide receiver to be taken in the 2011 NFL Draft, behind only [[A. J. Green]] of the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], who was selected fourth overall. In addition, he was one of five Alabama Crimson Tide players to be selected that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/draft.htm|title=2011 NFL Draft Listing|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones wears #11 with the Falcons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Behind-the-Jersey-Number-Julio-Jones/f4bb9599-f1cb-4df1-ae52-d11fc88aaa74|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814022353/http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Behind-the-Jersey-Number-Julio-Jones/f4bb9599-f1cb-4df1-ae52-d11fc88aaa74|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 14, 2017|title=Behind the Jersey Number: Julio Jones|last=Ferrin|first=Reid|date=October 14, 2014|publisher=Atlanta Falcons|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2011: Rookie year===\nJones came to terms with the Atlanta Falcons on July 28, 2011, signing a four-year contract worth $16.2 million, all of which was guaranteed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-falcons/falcons-sign-clabo-jones-1056157.html?cxtype=rss_news |title=Falcons sign Clabo, Jones and Rodgers |last=Ledbetter |first=D. Orlando |date=July 28, 2011 |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> His NFL debut came against the [[2011 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] at [[Soldier Field]]. In the 30\u201312 loss, he had five receptions for 71 yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109110chi.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Chicago Bears \u2013 September 11th, 2011|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In Week 4, against the [[2011 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]], he had 11 receptions for 127 yards in the 30\u201328 victory for his first game going over the century mark.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110020sea.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at Seattle Seahawks - October 2nd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> He recorded his first two NFL touchdowns on Week 9 of the [[2011 NFL season|2011 season]], against the [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] in a 31\u20137 victory. Jones's first touchdown was a 50-yard reception from quarterback [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] in the first quarter, and the second touchdown was an 80-yard reception from Ryan in the second quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111060clt.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 6th, 2011|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> After having quiet games against the [[2011 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111130atl.htm|title=New Orleans Saints at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 13th, 2011|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> and the [[2011 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111270atl.htm|title=Minnesota Vikings at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 27th, 2011|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones bounced back against the [[2011 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] with four receptions for 68 yards in the 17\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040htx.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Houston Texans \u2013 December 4th, 2011|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones finished his rookie season strong by combining for 393 receiving yards and six touchdowns over the last four games of the regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02/gamelog/2011|title=Julio Jones 2011 Game Log|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He finished the season leading all rookies in touchdown receptions with eight, while his 54 receptions for 959 yards ranked him second among rookies in yards and touchdowns, behind [[A. J. Green]], of the [[2011 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] and third in catches behind Green and [[Greg Little (wide receiver)|Greg Little]], of the [[2011 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/YEgBn |title=Rookies sorted by receiving yards, 2011 season |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He was named to the NFL All-Rookie Team for the 2011 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/nfl-all-rookie-2011.htm |title=2011 NFL All-Rookie Team |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Falcons made the playoffs with a 10\u20136 record to earn the #5-seed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011 |title=2011 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> In his playoff debut, Jones had seven receptions for 64 yards in a 24\u20132 [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#NFC: New York Giants 24, Atlanta Falcons 2|Wild Card Round]] loss to the eventual [[Super Bowl XLVI|Super Bowl]] champion [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201080nyg.htm|title=Wild Card \u2013 Atlanta Falcons at New York Giants \u2013 January 8th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nJones started his second professional season against the [[2012 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] with six receptions for 108 yards and two touchdowns in the 40\u201324 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090kan.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 September 9th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On October 28, against the [[2012 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] in Week 8, Jones had five receptions for 123 yards and a touchdown in the 30\u201317 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210280phi.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Philadelphia Eagles \u2013 October 28th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> The following week, he backed up his performance against the Eagles with five receptions for 129 yards against the [[2012 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] in the 19\u201313 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211040atl.htm|title=Dallas Cowboys at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 4th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On October 25, against the [[2012 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Jones had six receptions for 147 yards and a touchdown in the 24\u201323 victory in Week 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211250tam.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 November 25th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On December 16, against the defending Super Bowl champion [[2012 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Jones had six receptions for 74 yards and two touchdowns in the 34\u20130 victory in Week 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212160atl.htm|title=New York Giants at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 December 16th, 2012|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Falcons finished the season with a 13\u20133 record and earned the top seed in the NFC for the [[National Football League playoffs|NFL playoffs]]. In the [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs#NFC: Atlanta Falcons 30, Seattle Seahawks 28|Divisional Round]] against the [[2012 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Jones recorded his first career interception on the last play of the game defending a [[Hail Mary pass]] attempt from quarterback [[Russell Wilson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/01/nfl_report_role_reversal_for_f.html |title=NFL Report: Role reversal for Foley's Julio Jones in Falcons' playoff victory |last=Inabinett |first=Mark |date=January 13, 2013 |website=AL.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 12, 2019}}</ref> In addition, he recorded six receptions for 59 yards in the 30\u201328 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301130atl.htm|title=Divisional Round \u2013 Seattle Seahawks at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 January 13th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship Game: San Francisco 49ers 28, Atlanta Falcons 24|NFC Championship]] against the [[2012 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Jones had 11 receptions for 182 yards and two touchdowns in the 28\u201324 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301200atl.htm|title=NFC Championship \u2013 San Francisco 49ers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 January 20th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2012 season, Jones had 79 receptions for 1,198 yards and 10 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02/gamelog/2012|title=Julio Jones 2012 Game Log|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> As a result of his successful season, he was selected for the [[2013 Pro Bowl]], which was his first [[Pro Bowl]] nomination.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/probowl.htm |title=2012 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> Jones and fellow wide receiver [[Roddy White]] were the first 1,000-yard receiving tandem the Falcons have had since [[1998 Atlanta Falcons season|1998]] ([[Tony Martin (American football)|Tony Martin]] and [[Terance Mathis]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/atl/1998.htm|title=1998 Atlanta Falcons Statistics & Players|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He was ranked 26th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2012]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/atlanta-falcons/0ap2000000210554/Champ-Bailey-Harry-Douglas-Ronde-Barber-Richard-Sherman |title='Top 100 Players of 2013': Julio Jones |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\n\nJones started the 2013 season with a solid performance against the [[2013 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] with seven receptions for 76 yards and a touchdown in the 23\u201317 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080nor.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at New Orleans Saints \u2013 September 8th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> The following week, Jones had 11 receptions for 182 yards and a touchdown against [[2013 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309150atl.htm|title=St. Louis Rams at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 15th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Over the next two games, Jones continued his hot streak with a 115-yard performance against the [[2013 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309220mia.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Miami Dolphins \u2013 September 22nd, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> and a 108-yard performance against the [[2013 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309290atl.htm|title=New England Patriots at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 29th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> However, on October 7, 2013, Jones fractured his foot in the Week 5 ''Monday Night Football'' loss to the [[2013 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] and would be out for the season. In that last game, he had eight receptions for 99 yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310070atl.htm|title=New York Jets at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 October 7th, 2013|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/9792368/julio-jones-atlanta-falcons-feared-done-remainder-season-foot-injury-source-confirms |title=Source: Falcons' Jones could miss season |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=2013-10-08 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Despite only playing five games due to injury, Jones still managed to finish 76th in receiving yards among 458 qualified players for the 2013 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/RWSx0 |title=2013 Season, Receiving |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\nOn April 29, 2014, the Falcons accepted the fifth-year option of Jones's rookie contract, extending his obligations with the team through the 2015 season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Adams |first=Jay |url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Falcons-Exercise-Fifth-Year-on-Jones/858e848d-8db2-4e62-bcf1-1868d59fb943 |title=Falcons Exercise Fifth Year on Jones |work=Atlanta Falcons |access-date=April 7, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813012154/http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Falcons-Exercise-Fifth-Year-on-Jones/858e848d-8db2-4e62-bcf1-1868d59fb943 |archive-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones started the 2014 season with a seven-reception, 116-yard performance against the [[2014 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]] at the [[Georgia Dome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070atl.htm|title=New Orleans Saints at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 7th, 2014|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He caught his first touchdown of the season the following week against the [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140cin.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 September 14th, 2014|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In the next game, against the [[2014 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', Jones had nine receptions for 161 yards and two touchdowns in the 56\u201314 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409180atl.htm|title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 18th, 2014|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Over the next few weeks, Jones would string some solid performances together, but no touchdowns. However, on November 30, Jones set a new career-high with 189 receiving yards on 10 receptions in the 29\u201318 victory over the [[2014 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411300atl.htm|title=Arizona Cardinals at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 30th, 2014|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> The following week on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', he once again broke his single game receiving record, recording 259 yards on 11 receptions in a 43\u201337 loss to the [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412080gnb.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Green Bay Packers \u2013 December 8th, 2014|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In the loss, Jones recorded the fourth most receiving yards in a ''Monday Night Football'' game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/r6P0f |title=Most receiving yards recorded on a Monday, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref> He finished the season with 104 receptions for 1,593 yards,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02/gamelog/2014|title=Julio Jones 2014 Game Log|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> first in the NFC in both categories and third in the entire NFL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/receiving.htm|title=2014 NFL Receiving|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He was named to the Pro Bowl for the 2014 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/probowl.htm |title=2014 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 13th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2015]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2015/0ap3000000499581/Top-100-Players-of-2015-No-13-Julio-Jones |title='Top 100 Players of 2015': No. 13 Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Julio Jones |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season===\nOn August 29, 2015, the Falcons signed Jones to a 5-year, $71.5 million extension with $47 million guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/13540272/julio-jones-atlanta-falcons-agree-five-year-contract-extension |title=Julio Jones, Atlanta Falcons agree to five-year contract extension |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=August 29, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=August 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones started the 2015 season with a strong performance against the [[2015 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] on ''Monday Night Football''. In the 26\u201324 victory, Jones had nine receptions for 141 yards and two touchdowns to earn his first NFC Offensive Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509140atl.htm|title=Philadelphia Eagles at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 14th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_1.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 1 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> After a career-high 13 receptions for 135 yards in a 24\u201320 victory over the [[2015 New York Giants season|Giants]] in Week 2,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200nyg.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at New York Giants \u2013 September 20th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones recorded a 164-yard and two-touchdown performance in the 39\u201328 victory over the [[2015 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]. Jones was targeted a career-high 20 times in the victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270dal.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Dallas Cowboys \u2013 September 27th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In Week 5, against the [[2015 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]], Jones had five receptions for 67 yards but scored an unusual touchdown on an offensive fumble recovery in the end zone in the 25\u201319 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510110atl.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Atlanta Falcons - October 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> On November 1, in a 23\u201320 loss to the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Jones had 12 receptions for 162 yards and one touchdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511010atl.htm|title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 1st, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> After recording ten receptions for 137 yards in a performance in a 17\u201316 loss to the [[2015 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] the following week,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511080sfo.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at San Francisco 49ers \u2013 November 8th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Jones recorded nine receptions for 160 yards in a 24\u201321 loss to the [[2015 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511220atl.htm|title=Indianapolis Colts at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 November 22nd, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, against the [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Jones had nine receptions for 118 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200jax.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 20th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> The following week, Jones had nine receptions for 178 yards and a touchdown in a 20\u201313 victory over the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512270atl.htm|title=Carolina Panthers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 December 27th, 2015|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_16.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 16 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> In the season finale, against the [[2015 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Jones finished his historic season with nine receptions for 149 yards in the 20\u201317 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601030atl.htm|title=New Orleans Saints at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 January 3rd, 2016|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones finished the 2015 season with 1,871 yards, a Falcons franchise record and the second-highest in NFL history, behind [[Calvin Johnson]] (1,964 receiving yards in [[2012 NFL season|2012]] for the [[2012 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]]). He had a franchise record 136 receptions, tying with [[Antonio Brown]] of the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] for the most receptions that season<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/receiving.htm|title=2015 NFL Receiving|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> and the second highest in NFL history, behind [[Marvin Harrison]] (143 receptions in [[2002 NFL season|2002]] with the [[2002 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]). He was selected to the [[2015 Pro Bowl]], the third of his career, and earned [[2015 All-Pro Team|first-team All-Pro]] honors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/probowl.htm |title=2015 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/allpro.htm |title=2015 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked by his fellow players as the eighth best player on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000673247/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-8-Julio-Jones |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 8 Julio Jones |website=NFL.com |access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season: Super Bowl appearance===\n\n====Regular season====\n\nJones started the 2016 season with a four-reception, 66-yard, one-touchdown performance in a 31\u201324 loss to the [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in the last regular-season opener at the Georgia Dome.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/tampa-bay-buccaneers/os-ap-bucs-top-falcons-opener-31-24-20160911-story.html |title=Jameis Winston's 4 TD passes push Bucs past Falcons 31-24 in opener |last=Odum |first=Charles |date=September 11, 2016 |website=Orlando Sentinel |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> The following week, Jones had five receptions for 106 yards and a touchdown in a 35\u201328 road win over the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tdalabamamag.com/2016/09/18/wide-receiver-julio-jones-leads-atlanta-falcons-to-road-win-over-oakland-raiders/ |title=Wide receiver Julio Jones leads Atlanta Falcons to road win over Oakland Raiders |last=Smith |first=Stephen M. |date=September 19, 2016 |website=Touchdown Alabama |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4, Jones caught 12 passes for a Falcons-record 300 yards and a touchdown in a 48\u201333 victory over the [[2016 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2667297-julio-jones-becomes-sixth-receiver-with-300-yard-game |title=Julio Jones Becomes 6th Receiver with 300-Yard Game |date=October 4, 2016 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> His performance against the Panthers made Jones the sixth player in NFL history ever to have at least 300 receiving yards in a game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000713849/article/matt-ryan-julio-jones-set-records-in-win-over-panthers |title=Matt Ryan, Julio Jones set records in win over Panthers |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=October 2, 2016 |work=NFL.com |access-date=April 7, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> He earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/week_4.htm |title=2016 NFL Week 4 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> In addition, [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] threw for 503 passing yards, making them the first quarterback/wide receiver duo to gain 500+ passing yards and 300+ receiving yards in a single NFL game. On October 16, in a 26\u201324 loss to the [[2016 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Jones had seven receptions for 139 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610160sea.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Seattle Seahawks \u2013 October 16th, 2016|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> He followed up his performance against the Seahawks with a 174-yard performance in a 33\u201330 loss to the [[2016 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610230atl.htm|title=San Diego Chargers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 October 23rd, 2016|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> On November 3, in the second game against Tampa Bay, Jones had eight receptions for 111 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201611030tam.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 November 3rd, 2016|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Against the [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] on November 13, Jones had a 135-yard performance on ten receptions in the 24\u201315 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201611130phi.htm|title=Atlanta Falcons at Philadelphia Eagles \u2013 November 13th, 2016|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones finished the 2016 season with 83 receptions on 129 targets for 1,409 yards and six touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02/gamelog/2016|title=Julio Jones 2016 Game Log|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> His 17.0 yards per reception and 10.9 yards per target were career highs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.playerprofiler.com/nfl/julio-jones |title=Julio Jones Advanced Stats and Metrics Profile: Efficiency |website=PlayerProfiler.com |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> Jones was selected to his third consecutive and fourth career Pro Bowl and was named First-team [[2016 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] for the second consecutive year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/probowl.htm |title=2016 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/allpro.htm |title=2016 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770458/article/three-rookies-matt-ryan-among-players-named-to-allpro-team?campaign=Twitter_atn |title=Three rookies, Matt Ryan among players named to All-Pro team |date=January 6, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 18, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He was also ranked third by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]] as the highest ranked wide receiver.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000817553/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-3-Julio-Jones |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 3 Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Julio Jones |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Postseason====\nThe Falcons made the playoffs in the 2016 season and had the #2 seed in the NFC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/playoffs.htm |title=2016 NFL Playoff Standings |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#NFC: Atlanta Falcons 36, Seattle Seahawks 20|Divisional Round]] against the Seahawks, Jones had six receptions for 67 yards and a touchdown in the 36\u201320 victory at the Georgia Dome.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ryan-silences-critics-as-falcons-advance-in-nfc-over-seahawks-36-20-1484452038 |title=Ryan Silences Critics as Falcons Advance in NFC Over Seahawks, 36-20 |last=Chairusmi |first=Jim |date=January 14, 2017 |website=Wall Street Journal |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship Game: Atlanta Falcons 44, Green Bay Packers 21|NFC Championship]] against the [[2016 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], Jones had nine receptions for 180 yards and two touchdowns in the 44\u201321 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/2017/1/22/16043616/julio-jones-atlanta-falcons-green-bay-packers-nfc-title-game-badc7fc3d8c |title=Julio Jones Demolished the Packers |last=Sherman |first=Rodger |date=January 22, 2017 |website=The Ringer |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> During [[Super Bowl LI]] against the [[2016 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Jones had four receptions for 87 receiving yards on only four targets as the Falcons lost in overtime by a score of 34\u201328. Late in the game, with the Falcons leading 28\u201320, Jones recorded a spectacular catch from Ryan to put the Falcons on the Patriots 22-yard line. However, a sack and a holding penalty caused the Falcons to lose field position and move out of field goal range.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2017/02/06/julio-jones-made-an-iconic-catch-and-then-the-falcons-blew-the-super-bowl/ |title=Julio Jones made an iconic catch. Then the Falcons blew the Super Bowl. |last=Kilgore |first=Adam |date=February 6, 2017 |work=Washington Post |access-date=December 25, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI \u2013 New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons \u2013 February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000783872/article/falcons-historic-collapse-leads-to-patriots-fifth-super-bowl-win |title=Falcons' historic collapse leads to Patriots' fifth Super Bowl win |last=Chadiha |first=Jeffri |date=February 6, 2017 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\nOn September 10, 2017, in the season opener against the [[2017 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], Jones started the season with four receptions for 66 yards in the 23\u201317 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2017/09/10/ryan-leads-2-td-drives-in-4th-falcons-beat-bears-23-17/105476896/ |title=Ryan leads 2 TD drives in 4th, Falcons hold off Bears 23-17 |date=September 10, 2017 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 2, in the 34\u201323 victory over the [[2017 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], he had five receptions for 108 yards in the first game in the new [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/football/report-card-falcons-packers/E00cd4WsDGJu3G8RDCpAEL/ |title=Report card: Falcons 34, Packers 23 |last=Ledbetter |first=D. Orlando |website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |language=English |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> In Week 7, in a loss to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] in a Super Bowl LI rematch, Jones recorded his first receiving touchdown of the 2017 season, a one-yard reception from Ryan. During Week 12 against the [[2017 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Jones had a monstrous performance with 12 receptions for 253 receiving yards and two touchdowns, of which one thrown from fellow receiver [[Mohamed Sanu]], as the Falcons won 34\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2017/11/26/jones-big-game-leads-falcons-past-buccaneers-34-20/108057040/ |title=Julio Jones' 253 yards and two TDs lead Falcons past Buccaneers 34-20 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> His performance in Week 12 earned him NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000885090/article/philip-rivers-phil-dawson-lead-players-of-the-week |title=Philip Rivers, Phil Dawson lead Players of the Week |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=November 30, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> Jones became the first player in NFL history with three games with at least 250 receiving yards and the tenth to record three games with at least 200.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/yQqoi |title=Most games with at least 250 receiving yards, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/1UOZG |title=Most games with at least 200 receiving yards, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>  On December 19, 2017, Jones was named to his fifth Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters |title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters |date=December 19, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> In the Week 17 regular season finale against the [[2017 New Orleans Saints|New Orleans Saints]], he had seven receptions for 149 yards in the 23\u201313 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712240nor.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at New Orleans Saints - December 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOverall, he finished the 2017 season with 88 receptions for 1,444 receiving yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02/gamelog/2017/ |title=Julio Jones 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> The Falcons made the playoffs and faced off against the Los Angeles Rams in the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC: Atlanta Falcons 26, Los Angeles Rams 13|Wild Card Round]]. Against the Rams, he had 94 receiving yards and a touchdown in the 26\u201313 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/sports/atlanta-falcons-win-over-los-angeles-rams/2062231/ |title=Matt Ryan Leads Falcons\u2019 26-13 Playoff Win Over Upstart LA Rams |website=NBC Bay Area |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC: Philadelphia Eagles 15, Atlanta Falcons 10|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], he had 101 receiving yards but the Falcons lost by a score of 15\u201310.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/sports/other_sports/jalen-mills-on-the-last-play-when-julio-jones-came-up-short-20180113.html |title=Eagles' corner Jalen Mills came up big on last play, when Julio Jones came up short |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Frank |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> He was targeted in the endzone on the Falcons' final offensive play but the pass from Ryan went barely through his hands.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-playoffs-falcons-final-play-a-disaster-eagles-knew-before-they-broke-the-huddle/ |title=NFL Playoffs: Falcons final play a disaster, Eagles knew 'before they broke the huddle' |last=Brinson |first=Will |date=January 14, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked fourth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000938442/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Julio-Jones-No-4 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Julio Jones  |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\nIn the season-opener against the defending [[Super Bowl LII|Super Bowl]] champions, the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Jones recorded 10 receptions for 169 yards to go with an 11-yard rush in the 12\u201318 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000959095/article/lack-of-clear-proof-results-in-no-catch-for-julio-jones |title=Lack of clear proof results in no catch for Julio Jones |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=September 7, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2794620-eagles-hang-on-to-beat-julio-jones-falcons-18-12-on-thursday-night-football |title=Eagles Hang On to Beat Julio Jones, Falcons 18\u201312 on Thursday Night Football |last=Polacek |first=Scott |date=September 6, 2018 |work=Bleacher Report |access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref> In the loss, Jones became the first player in franchise history to record 40 games with at least 100 receiving yards, breaking his tie with Roddy White.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefalcoholic.com/2018/9/9/17833744/julio-jones-atlanta-falcons-receiving-yards-record-100-yards-roddy-white |title=Julio Jones broke the franchise record for 100-yard receiving games Thursday |last=Ikic |first=Adnan |date=September 9, 2018 |website=The Falcoholic |language=en |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4, he recorded nine receptions for 173 receiving yards in the 37\u201336 loss to the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/152987b980724cc5ad90df792a025c4b/Dalton%2527s-late-TD-pass-to-Green-lifts-Bengals-over-Falcons |title=Dalton's late TD pass to Green lifts Bengals over Falcons |last=Odum |first=Charles |date=September 30, 2018 |work=AP NEWS |access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> In Week 6, against the [[2018 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had 10 receptions for 144 yards in the 34\u201329 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201810140atl.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Atlanta Falcons - October 14th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> In Week 9 against the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], Jones caught seven passes for 121 yards and his first receiving touchdown of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/breakingnews/story/2018/nov/04/julio-jones-finally-scores/482405/ |title=Julio Jones finally scores a touchdown as Falcons blow out Redskins |date=November 4, 2018 |website=Chattanooga Times Free Press |access-date=December 5, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 10, against the [[2018 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Jones recorded seven receptions for 107 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cleveland.com/sports/2018/11/julio-jones-sets-milestone-but-focus-is-on-loss-to-cleveland-browns-video.html |title=Julio Jones sets milestone, but focus is on loss to Cleveland Browns (video) |last=Wright |first=Branson |date=November 11, 2018 |website=cleveland.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In that game, Jones became the fastest player in NFL history to reach 10,000 career receiving yards, accomplishing the feat in 104 games, beating out [[Calvin Johnson]] who took 115 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/atlanta-falcons/post/_/id/33343/julio-jones-becomes-fastest-receiver-to-10000-yards |title=Julio Jones becomes fastest receiver to 10,000 yards |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=November 11, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> In the following game, against the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], he had six receptions for 118 yards and a touchdown in the loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thefalconswire.usatoday.com/2018/11/19/falcons-highlights-the-best-of-julio-jones-vs-cowboys/ |title=Falcons Highlights: The best of Julio Jones vs. Cowboys |last=Weaver |first=Tim |date=November 19, 2018 |website=Falcons Wire |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In Week 12, against the [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] on Thanksgiving, he had 11 receptions for 147 yards in the 31\u201317 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.numberfire.com/nfl/player-news/104188/julio-jones-catches-11-passes-for-147-yards-falcons-fall-to-saints |title=Julio Jones catches 11 passes for 147 yards, Falcons fall to Saints |last=Levinson |first=Josh |date=November 23, 2018 |website=numberFire |language=en-us |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In Week 14, against the [[2018 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], he had eight receptions for 106 yards and two touchdowns. Jones eclipsed 1,400 yards and became the first player in NFL history to register five consecutive seasons with at least 1,400 yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/football/jones-first-player-nfl-history-with-more-than-400-yards-receiving-five-consecutive-seasons/1j0RCRqgJr0D4V9aJ75xQO/|title=Falcons\u2019 Julio Jones sets NFL record with another 1,400-yard season|last=D. Orlando Ledbetter|first=|date=December 10, 2018|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> In Week 17, against the [[2018 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had 138 yards and a touchdown in the 34\u201332 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812300tam.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - December 30th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> On December 18, 2018, Jones was named to his sixth [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]], which he declined due to injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001001792/article/nfl-reveals-rosters-for-2019-pro-bowl-in-orlando |title=NFL reveals rosters for 2019 Pro Bowl in Orlando |date=December 18, 2018 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2019/01/julio-jones-to-sit-out-pro-bowl.html |title=Julio Jones to sit out Pro Bowl |last=Inabinett |first=Mark |date=January 7, 2019 |website=AL.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJones finished the 2018 season with 113 receptions for a league-leading 1,677 yards and eight receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2018/12/alabama-nfl-roundup-julio-jones-earns-receiving-title.html |title=Alabama NFL roundup: Julio Jones earns receiving title |last=Inabinett |first=Mark |date=December 31, 2018 |website=al.com |language=en-US |access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02.htm|title=Julio Jones 2018 Game Log|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> Jones was the only player during the 2018 season to average more than 100 receiving yards per game with 104.8 yards per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/receiving.htm|title=2018 NFL Receiving|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> Despite not recording a single touchdown reception during the first eight weeks of the season, Jones had eight touchdown catches in the final eight weeks of the season, the most out of any player during that span.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spark.adobe.com/page/NFPdJfSeHeTvE/|title=Postgame Notes: Atlanta at Tampa Bay|website=spark.adobe.com|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked ninth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thefalconswire.usatoday.com/2019/07/31/falcons-julio-jones-nfl-top-100-list-2019-ranking/ |title=Julio Jones gets another top-10 ranking on NFL Top 100 list for 2019 |last=Weaver |first=Tim |date=August 1, 2019 |website=Falcons Wire |language=en |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2019/0ap3000001038312/Top-100-Players-of-2019-Julio-Jones-No-9 |title='Top 100 Players of 2019': Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Julio Jones |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nOn September 7, 2019, Jones signed a three-year, $66 million extension with $64 million guaranteed, making him the highest paid wide receiver in the league.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051676/article/falcons-wr-julio-jones-set-to-sign-3yr-66m-deal |title=Falcons WR Julio Jones set to sign 3-yr, $66M deal |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=September 7, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn Week 1 against the [[2019 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Jones had six receptions for 31 yards and his first receiving touchdown of the season as the Falcons lost 12\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127961 |title=Vikings trample Falcons 28-12 behind fierce defense, Cook |date=September 8, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[2019 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Jones recorded five receptions for 106 yards and two touchdowns as the Falcons won 24\u201320. Jones' second touchdown occurred on fourth down with two minutes left in the game. On the play, quarterback [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] threw a short pass to Jones which he ran in for a 54-yard touchdown that ended up sealing a Falcons win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128124 |title=Jones scores late TD, leads Falcons past Eagles 24-20 |last=Newberry |first=Paul |date=September 15, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 15, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27626806/jones-sets-falcons-career-receiving-yards-record |title=Jones sets Falcons' career receiving-yards record |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=September 15, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> In this game, Jones became the Falcons all-time receiving yard leader, surpassing the record previously set by [[Roddy White]]. In Week 3 against the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], Jones caught eight passes for 128 yards and one touchdown as the Falcons lost 24\u201327.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127929 |title=Brissett's fast start helps Colts hold off Falcons 27-24 |date=September 22, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 22, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 4, Jones became the fastest player in NFL history to reach 11,000 career receiving yards, doing so in 115 games, beating out [[Calvin Johnson]] who took 127 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/julio-jones-becomes-fastest-receiver-to-reach-11-000-yards?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Julio Jones becomes fastest receiver to reach 11,000 yards |website=Atlanta Falcons |language=en-US |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> In Week 8 against the [[2019 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]], Jones had 10 receptions for 152 yards in the 27\u221220 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128035 |title=Wilson throws 2 TD passes as Seattle stops Atlanta 27-20 |date=October 27, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=October 27, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Jones had to miss the Week 12 game against the [[2019 New Orleans Saints|New Orleans Saints]] due to a shoulder injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001081418/article/injuries-falcons-wr-julio-jones-ruled-out-vs-saints |title=Injuries: Falcons WR Julio Jones ruled out vs. Saints |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> In Week 15 against the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Jones had a season-high 13 receptions for 134 receiving yards and two touchdowns, the latter of which was the game winner, in the 29\u221222 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128108 |title=Matt Ryan, Falcons rally in final seconds, stun 49ers 29-22 |date=December 15, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=December 16, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 16 against the [[2019 Jacksonville Jaguars|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Jones was targeted a career-high 20 times and recorded 10 receptions for a season-high 166 receiving yards as the Falcons won 24\u201312. In the game, Jones became the fastest player in NFL history to reach 12,000 career receiving yards, accomplishing the feat in 125 games, beating out [[Jerry Rice]] who took 142 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/julio-jones-surpasses-jerry-rice-as-fastest-player-to-12-000-receiving-yards?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Julio Jones surpasses Jerry Rice as fastest player to 12,000 receiving yards |last=McFadden |first=Will |date=December 22, 2019 |website=Atlanta Falcons |language=en-US |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\nJones finished the 2019 season with 99 receptions for 1,394 receiving yards and six receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JoneJu02.htm |title=Julio Jones 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> He finished second in the league in receiving yards and sixth in receptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2019/receiving.htm |title=2019 NFL Receiving |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> He earned his seventh career nomination to the Pro Bowl for his 2019 campaign, but he elected not to go.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/julio-jones-on-seventh-pro-bowl-nod-passing-jerry-rice-s-record?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Julio Jones on seventh Pro Bowl nod, passing Jerry Rice\u2019s record |last=Conway |first=Kelsey |website=Atlanta Falcons |language=en-US |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|<center>Legend</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em\"|\n|NFL record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n{| class= \"wikitable\" float=\"left\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"18\" style=\"background: #BD0D18; border: 2px solid #000000; color: #FFFFFF;\" |<center>'''NFL career statistics'''</center>\n|-\n!colspan=4|Season !! colspan=\"6\" |Receiving !! colspan=\"6\" |Rushing !! colspan=\"2\" |Fumbles\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Y/G !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Y/G !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n![[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]\n| 13 || 13 || 54 || 959 || '''17.8''' || 73.8 || 80T || 8 || 6 || 56 || 9.3 || 4.3 || 19 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n![[2012 NFL season|2012]] !! [[2012 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]\n| 16 || 15 || 79 || 1,198 || 15.2 || 74.9 || 80T ||'''10''' || 6 || 30 || 5.0 || 1.9 || 