 NBA All-Star Game|2005]], [[2006 NBA All-Star Game|2006]], [[2007 NBA All-Star Game|2007]], [[2008 NBA All-Star Game|2008]], [[2009 NBA All-Star Game|2009]], [[2010 NBA All-Star Game|2010]], [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011]], [[2012 NBA All-Star Game|2012]], [[2014 NBA All-Star Game|2014]], [[2015 NBA All-Star Game|2015]], [[2019 NBA All-Star Game|2019]] \n*[[Josh Howard]] \u2013 2007\n*[[Luka Don\u010di\u0107]] \u2013 2020\n\n;[[List of NBA All-Star Game head coaches]]\n*[[Don Nelson]] \u2013 [[2002 NBA All-Star Game|2002]]\n*[[Avery Johnson]] \u2013 [[2006 NBA All-Star Game|2006]]\n\n==Management==\n[[Mark Cuban]] purchased a majority stake in the Mavericks for $280&nbsp;million from [[Ross Perot Jr.]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Perot sells Mavs to Internet mogul|url=http://amarillo.com/stories/012100/spo_LS0517.001.shtml#.WpVNV-eYP4Y|website=Amarillo.com|accessdate=February 27, 2018|date=January 21, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/dallas/columns/story?id=4793301|title=Mavs under Cuban: 10 wild years|date=January 3, 2010|publisher=ESPN|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Terdema Ussery===\n[[Terdema Ussery]] served as team president and CEO from 1997 until 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chatsports.com/dallas-mavericks/a/source/mavericks-source-longtime-team-presidentceo-terdema-ussery-to-resign-today-11592132|title=Mavericks source: Longtime team president/CEO Terdema Ussery to resign today|last=News|first=Dallas Morning|date=July 16, 2015|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> During this time Ussery also served in other roles, including president of the Dallas Mavericks Foundation and an alternate governor for the Mavericks on the NBA Board of Governors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leadersmag.com/issues/2008.3_july/dallas/ussery.html|title=Leaders July 2008 \u2013 An Interview with Terdema L. Ussery II, President and Chief Executive Officer, Dallas Mavericks, and Chief Executive Officer, HDNet|website=LeadersMag.com|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> Ussery left the Mavericks for a position with [[Under Armour]].\n\n===Sexual assault and domestic violence allegations===\nIn February 2018, the Dallas Mavericks hired former AT&T executive Cynthia Marshall as their interim CEO in a direct response to the franchise's sexual assault and domestic violence allegations involving Ussery and Earl K. Sneed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/mavericks/2018/02/25/dallas-mavericks-name-new-interim-ceo-wake-scandal/371670002/|title=Dallas Mavericks to name new interim CEO in wake of scandal|work=USA Today|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2018/02/20/dallas-mavericks-sexual-misconduct-investigation-mark-cuban-response|title=Exclusive: Inside the Mavericks' corrosive workplace|work=Sports Illustrated|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> Marshall was the first black female CEO of an NBA franchise as well as the first woman ever to hold the position.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sacobserver.com/2018/05/first-black-female-ceo-of-the-nba-honored-at-state-capitol/|title=First Black Female CEO of the NBA Honored at State Capitol|website=SacObserver.com|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOwner Mark Cuban formally responded in March 2018 to allegations of a 2011 sexual assault that surfaced in a [[Sports Illustrated]] investigation released in February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2018/02/20/mark-cuban-mavericks-response-dallas-mavericks-statement-sexual-misconduct|title=Mark Cuban responds to SI's Mavs investigation|work=Sports Illustrated|access-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref> In an email to [[Associated Press|The Associated Press]] on March 6, Cuban stated, \"It didn't happen.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/mavericks-owner-mark-cuban-denies-sexual-assault-allegation-resurfaced-from-2011/|title=Mavericks owner Mark Cuban denies sexual assault allegation resurfaced from 2011|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref> The organization hired a pair of independent investigators to look into allegations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/dallas-mavericks/mavericks/2018/05/09/latest-mavs-sexual-harassment-investigation-cynthia-marshall-provides-update|title=What's the latest on the Mavs' sexual harassment investigation? Cynthia Marshall provides an update|date=May 9, 2018|work=SportsDay|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref> On September 19, 2018, the team's investigation report concluded that there were \"numerous instances of sexual harassment and other improper workplace conduct\" that had occurred within the organization, none of which being related to the allegation on Cuban himself. Cuban also agreed to donate $10&nbsp;million in reparations to organizations related to women's causes, mainly those committed to combating domestic violence and supporting the professional development of women within the sports industry.\n\nOn October 5, 2018, over two weeks after the team publicly released their sexual harassment report, it was reported that team photographer Danny Bollinger, who had been friends with Mark Cuban, also made propositions to four now-former employees throughout an entire decade. Bollinger was also laid off by Cuban four days later.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Dallas Mavericks}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle = {{NBA color cell|Dallas Mavericks|border=2}}|list =\n{{Dallas Mavericks seasons}}\n{{NBA}}\n{{Texas sports}}\n{{Dallas}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks| ]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 1980]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Basketball in Dallas]]\n", "name_user": "2601:40c:8202:6eb0:8d41:e26b:4c77:d29a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas_Mavericks"}
